<FIRST>u a AM-TimberCompromise     07-14 0492</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Timber Compromise,0504</SECOND>
<HEAD>Environmental Groups Offer Plan Allowing Some Logging</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB BAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Environmentalists offered a plan Friday aimed at preserving ancient forests in the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Northwest </LOCATION> while allowing timber companies to cut down more trees. The federal government has been prevented from selling many older forest stands to timber companies because of court injunctions won by environmental groups, who argued the stands may be the last remaining habitat for the Northern spotted owl. The injunctions have drastically reduced the supply of logs for lumber mills in the Northwest. The plan offered Friday would release 490 million board feet of timber currently barred from logging under court injunctions. A compromise plan worked out at a meeting of environmentalists, timber industry officials and politicians last month went up in smoke when some environmental groups said it allowed for too much logging. Reaction to the latest proposal was mixed. `` I'm encouraged,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> DeFazio </PERSON>, D-Ore. `` I think it's a thoughtful albeit somewhat complicated response. But <PERSON> Rachel </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorlin </PERSON>, press secretary to Rep. <PERSON> Less </PERSON> <PERSON> AuCoin </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ore </LOCATION>, said: `` It raises as many questions as it seems to answer.'' And <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Geisinger </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forestry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, said the plan strayed too far from the original framework for the summit compromise. `` They want to be in charge of managing the national forests,'' said <PERSON> Geisinger </PERSON>, who represented the timber industry at the summit. `` I do n't think we are prepared to turn that responsibility over to them.'' Overall, the environmentalists offer would allow 9.6 billion board feet of federal timber to be harvested in <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> over the next 15 months. <PERSON> Andy </PERSON> <PERSON> Kerr </PERSON>, conservation dirrector of the <ORGANIZATION> Oregon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resouces </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, emphasized at a news conference Friday that the offer covered only the 1989 and 1990 fiscal years. The harvest level is 400 million board feet less than was proposed in the plan developed at the June 24 summit. Although the environmentalists called their proposal `` a minor reduction,'' congressional aides who asked not to be identified said the 400 million amounted to enough timber to supply four medium-sized mills with logs for a year. Under the plan, 3.7 billion board feet would be available for harvest in national forests the remainder of this fiscal year, 3.9 billion could be harvested on national forests in the 1990 fiscal year and a billion could be harvested on <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Land </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> land in each of the two fiscal years. `` A lot of this was difficult because we are bleeding,'' <PERSON> Kerr </PERSON> said. `` This plan is not sustainable for timber production and not sustainable for spotted owl production.'' Any long-term plan, he said, would have to provide more severe limits on federal logging, with a greater emphasis on improving production on private timberland. The plan would allow harvesting of small, fragmented stands; spotted owl habitat selected by environmentalists and areas that are not spotted owl habitat but have been protected by the injunctions.
</TEXT>
