<HEAD>Bomb Injures Seven American Soldiers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lead and 7th graf, `The three...' to UPDATE with four soldiers
in serious condition flown to U.S.; DELETES reference to Fort Kelly.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic NY31</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDDY CUEVAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A homemade bomb exploded outside a discotheque in northern <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> early Thursday and wounded seven <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> soldiers, four of them seriously, officials reported. Two other Americans in the group escaped injury. No one claimed responsibility for the fourth attack on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops in <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> since Feb. 1. `` Witnesses say the bomb was apparently thrown from a car, but the scenario is still confused,'' said <PERSON> Anne </PERSON> <PERSON> Sigmund </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION>. `` They do n't say if the bomb was thrown from a moving car or a parked car. We're still investigating.'' The soldiers had gone into <PERSON> La </PERSON> <PERSON> Ceiba </PERSON>, a coastal town 200 miles north of <LOCATION> Tegucigalpa </LOCATION>, in civilian dress and without proper leave, embassy spokesman <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Barclay </PERSON> said. `` They were not authorized to go into town,'' he said in a telephone interview. `` The group was part of a convoy carrying equipment and machinery from <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Castilla </LOCATION> to <PERSON> Enrique </PERSON> <PERSON> Soto </PERSON> <PERSON> Cano </PERSON> air base. I have no further details for the moment.'' Officials said the convoy of about 150 Americans was returning Wednesday from a road-building exercise with Honduran troops and stopped at <LOCATION> La </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ceiba </LOCATION> for the night. <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Castilla </LOCATION> is 250 miles north of <LOCATION> Tegucigalpa </LOCATION>. The four most seriously injured soldiers were flown to a military hospital in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Antonio </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, and the other three were being treated at <LOCATION> Soto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cano </LOCATION> 50 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Tegucigalpa </LOCATION>, the embassy said. The names were withheld pending notification of relatives. Col. <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanchez </PERSON>, the Honduran military commander at <LOCATION> La </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ceiba </LOCATION>, said by telephone the explosion occurred at the <LOCATION> Lido </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Discotheque </LOCATION>, and four Honduran suspects were being questioned. He would say nothing further about the suspects. <PERSON> Sanchez </PERSON> said the two uninjured soldiers were turned over to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officers from the <LOCATION> Soto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cano </LOCATION> base because `` they refused to talk and demanded a lawyer.'' The soldiers had been working in the <LOCATION> Valle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> del </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aguan </LOCATION>, 125 miles east of <LOCATION> La </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ceiba </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Barclay </PERSON> said. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has had facilities at the <ORGANIZATION> Soto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cano </ORGANIZATION> base in central <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> for years, and about 1,200 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military personnel are assigned there on six-month rotating tours. <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> has been the scene of frequent <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military exercises since 1982, in part as a political signal to the leftist <ORGANIZATION> Sandinista </ORGANIZATION> government in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, which borders <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> to the south. Many Hondurans resent the increased <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military role in the Central American nation, as well as the use of Honduran territory by U.S.-supported Contra rebels battling <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s government. On April 11, assailants attacked a jeep convoy carrying <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> soldiers outside <LOCATION> Olanchita </LOCATION>, near <LOCATION> La </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ceiba </LOCATION>. One jeep was disabled, but nobody was injured. On Feb. 1, assailants fired at an American military convoy in northern <PERSON> Yoro </PERSON> province. No one was injured. On Feb. 18, three <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> soldiers and two Honduran passers-by were wounded when a bomb was detonated under a passing bus in <LOCATION> Comayagua </LOCATION>, near <LOCATION> Soto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cano </LOCATION>. A shadowy leftist group calling itself the <ORGANIZATION> Morazanista </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> claimed responsibility for all three attacks this year and for attacks in 1983 and 1987. The group, formed in 1979 and named after <PERSON> Francisco </PERSON> <PERSON> Morazan </PERSON>, who ruled <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> from 1829 to 1832. It is believed to be part of the outlawed <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. In addition to the attacks on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military personnel, other violent incidents in <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> have raised fears of increased activity by left-wing guerrillas and right-wing death squads. Six people have been assassinated in the last three weeks, including a university professor shot to death Wednesday, a union leader and a student leader. On Jan. 25, former military chief Gen. <PERSON> Gustavo </PERSON> <PERSON> Alvarez </PERSON> <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> was assassinated. He helped found the Nicaraguan rebel movement in <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> while head of the military from 1982 to 1984.
</TEXT>
