<HEAD>Young American on the Road _ From Baseball to the Bolshoi</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE GOULD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Shannon </PERSON>, a determined teen-ager who says he `` left home at 14 forever'' in hopes of becoming a world-class dancer, is coming home to <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> _ with <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Bolshoi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ballet </ORGANIZATION> Five years after he said good-bye to his mother in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, he is back for a five-week, cross-country tour as the only <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> dancer with the <ORGANIZATION> Bolshoi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ballet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION>, the official school for what many consider the world's most prestigious ballet company. In the intervening years, always without family and usually without money, young <PERSON> Shannon </PERSON> worked and danced his way halfway around the world, being supported variously by the governments of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. He's also found himself in <LOCATION> Finland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION> and along the way learned to speak Russian, Hungarian and Italian. It's been, in a literal sense, a long leap. `` It's kind of strange,'' <PERSON> Shannon </PERSON> said in a backstage interview at suburban <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s Wolf Trap theater. `` I left home at 14 forever. Now I feel like a foreigner, coming back home.'' `` When I left, my mother said I'll miss you and love you, but I want you to have a better life than I have,'' <PERSON> Shannon </PERSON> said. `` I have no other family, we come from what you would call the lower end of the middle class, and she had to borrow money for my plane ticket.'' The first stop was <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> as he traded his <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> love of surfing, swimming and baseball for a chance to dance. `` I still did n't know if I'd make it,'' he says now. It was n't easy, even years later when he was discovered by <PERSON> Madame </PERSON> <PERSON> Sophia </PERSON> <PERSON> Golovkina </PERSON>, director of classical dance at the <ORGANIZATION> Moscow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Choreographic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> and a stern but loved master of the ballet. Now in her 70s, `` Madame Golovkina'' discovered <PERSON> Shannon </PERSON> at a ballet competition in <LOCATION> Jackson </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Miss. </LOCATION>, on one of his brief stopovers in this country since moving away. `` She's been like a mother to me ever since, and worked to get me accepted to the <ORGANIZATION> Bolshoi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION>,'' the rigorous training school for <ORGANIZATION> Bolshoi </ORGANIZATION> dancers, <PERSON> Shannon </PERSON> said. Already the recipient of an award from the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arts </ORGANIZATION> and the first American graduate of the <ORGANIZATION> Hungarian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ballet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Shannon </PERSON> scraped together some money, packed his bags and ent to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. `` There was no cultural exchange at that time,'' <PERSON> Shannon </PERSON> said. `` I was an exchange student without an exchange program and I spent every day going from one government ministry to another looking for support.'' `` I lived in a hotel, and on the last day when I ran out of money they called and said, `` You can stay,''' <PERSON> Shannon </PERSON> recalled, relief still clear in his voice. `` They do n't have any foreigners'' <PERSON> Shannon </PERSON> said of the academy, which was founded in 1773 and annually draws thousands of young Soviets hoping to be admitted as students. Although he has n't been formally admitted to the actual <ORGANIZATION> Bolshoi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ballet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Shannon </PERSON> hopes to win that honor during or shortly after the current <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> tour, the academy's first <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> visit in 20 years. `` I'd be the very first American. They've given me so much. I'd like to stay for years and bring what I've learned over there back here.'' The tour will take <PERSON> Shannon </PERSON> and company to <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, where he will be able to see, and perform for, his mother. Other stops include <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Indianapolis </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Madison </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wis. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paso </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Vail </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colo. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Binghamton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Shannon </PERSON> will dance with a troupe of other young, promising ballet stars, including 21-year-old <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> Malakhov </PERSON> and <PERSON> Galina </PERSON> <PERSON> Stepanyenko </PERSON>, 23, both winners of gold medals at the recent 6th <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> International Ballet competition. Both young stars have high hopes for continuing improvement in U.S.-Soviet relations, noting changes Miss <PERSON> Stepanyenko </PERSON> says `` are being felt all over the world.'' `` It is a difficult process, but we have muc