<HEAD>Maine Cracks Down on Blueberry Rustlers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GLENN ADAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AUGUSTA, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Rustlers are having a field day in <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>'s blueberry patches, raking up $ 1 million in purloined berries a year But the state is fighting back _ a new law gives police the ability to catch thieves blue-handed. Teams of blueberry thieves who scatter from pickup trucks can pick dozens of 24-pound boxes in a night, according to <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Jasper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wyman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Son of Milbridge, which harvests wild blueberries on 7,000 acres. The industry, fearing continued thievery during this summer's harvest, turned to the Legislature this spring for help Lawmakers passed a berry bill that was signed into law by Gov. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> McKernan </PERSON>. It is designed to give authorities the tools to track down the illegal pickers and end the black market _ make that blue market _ in berries. The law requires pickers to get written permission of landowners, and requires anyone who transports 25 pounds or more to get a numbered permit from the <ORGANIZATION> Maine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Blueberry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. Packers and shippers must also keep account of the blueberries they receive in lots of 25 pounds or more. Finally, the law authorizes police, sheriffs, forest rangers and game wardens to make inspections and arrests and investigate blueberry thefts. <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> is one of the nation's leading producers of blueberries, and they are one of its largest cash crops. Blueberries are a $ 70 million a year industry in the state, according to <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> McLaughlin </PERSON> of the blueberry commission. <PERSON> McLaughlin </PERSON> said thefts are worst in seasons when the price is highest. He estimated the loss during the 1988 season at $ 1 million. Suspected thieves confronted by <PERSON> Wyman </PERSON> employees typically claim they took the berries from someone else's fields, said <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON>. Others spotted in the act make easy getaways on the dirt roads that wind through the hilly barrens. `` These people are doing it for money,'' said <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON>, who added that organized thieves tend to go where the berries grow the best. `` It's a big business.'' While people in the industry say the law was a long time coming, some casual roadside pickers believe the state has gone too far. `` For heaven's sake, the most I would ever take is three or four quarts,'' said a woman who asked that her name not be used. `` They've roped off all of the good blueberry patches. I'm miffed. I'll just have to sneak in after dark.''
