<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-89 0311EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-AIDS     07-14 0640</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AIDS,0658</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mutant Proteins May Serve as AIDS Treatment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL Q. HANEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The discovery that experimental mutant proteins can stop the destructive multiplication of the AIDS virus may give scientists a new weapon in their search for drugs to tame the disease, scientists say. In reports in today's issue of the journal Cell, doctors said they crafted these proteins by tinkering with two genes of human immunodeficiency virus, which causes AIDS. While one of the researchers called the work `` a major step,'' others were more cautious, noting that any practical result of this work is probably years away. Some time in the distant future, however, doctors said these fake proteins could be the basis of a cure for acquired immune deficiency syndrome. In the work, scientists changed AIDS virus genes known as tat and rev. Both produce proteins that are essential for the virus to churn out new copies of itself inside the body. The scientists found that by slightly scrambling the genes, they can make them produce proteins that do n't work. But because the proteins look like the real thing, the AIDS virus is fooled into using them instead of its own natural proteins. As a result, virus replication is shut down. Dr. <PERSON> Maurice </PERSON> <PERSON> Green </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Louis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> experimented with the tat gene, and Dr. <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Cullen </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Howard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hughes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> at <ORGANIZATION> Duke </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> worked with the rev gene. <PERSON> Green </PERSON> said that unlike most proteins, the fake tat product can be taken in by cells. There it will `` jam up the virus control mechanism for viral replication.'' `` We are testing it out against the most virulent strains of AIDS virus, and we are very encouraged,'' said <PERSON> Green </PERSON>. `` It's a major step forward, as far as I'm concerned, in possible AIDS therapy.'' However, Dr. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Haseltine </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Dana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Farber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cancer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, a co-discoverer of both genes, cautioned, `` It's an interesting concept, but it's a long way from making a useful drug.'' The AIDS virus kills by slipping inside blood cells called T cells, subverting them to make new copies of the virus and then killing the cells. People eventually die largely because of the destruction of these blood cells, which are essential for fighting routine infections. The scientists' research suggests two possible ways to combat AIDS. One is to flood the bloodstream with fake viral proteins that will overwhelm the genuine product and short-circuit reproduction of the virus. The other, probably more difficult, approach is to implant the viral genes that make these bogus proteins into victims' bodies so they will produce their own anti-viral ammunition In the latter approach, scientists would implant mutant rev or tat genes into a patient's bone marrow tissue, which makes new blood cells. The new bone marrow would produce blood cells that carry the extra viral genes. When these cells got infected with the AIDS virus, they would not be killed. Instead, the added genes would make proteins that would keep the virus from reproducing and destroying the blood cells. `` You would end up with a population of T cells that are no longer sensitive to the HIV virus,'' said <PERSON> Cullen </PERSON>. `` At that point, you will have reconstituted the person's immune system and they should be in great shape. `` The long-term promise of this technology is that it's a cure, not just a treatment.'' But <PERSON> Cullen </PERSON> cautioned that this approach `` is a long, long way from reality,'' and no one even knows whether it will work. In the virus, the tat gene is a sort of supercharger, vastly speeding up its ability to make new copies of itself. Rev is an on-off switch. When rev is working, the virus will assemble the proteins it needs to make new copies. But when it's shut off, no new virus will be made.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
