<HEAD>EPA Naming Government Sites to Hazardous Waste List</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> is stepping in with everything but the money to clean up some of the worst-polluted military bases, nuclear weapons plants and nuclear laboratories run by the government. The <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> announced Thursday it plans to add 52 sites to its National Priorities List, the so-called Superfund list of hazardous waste sites needing the most attention. Among the sites are well-known laboratories and weapons materials plants such as <ORGANIZATION> Fernald </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Brookhaven </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Oak </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ridge </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Livermore </PERSON> in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. Military bases account for most of the 52. Estimates for cleaning up the radioactive and hazardous waste at all the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION>'s nuclear facilities range from $ 80 billion to $ 150 billion. <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> administrator <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Reilly </PERSON> said in a statement that many of the facilities `` are much larger and more complex than other Superfund sites, with wide varieties of hazardous and radioactive wastes.'' <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>, in its Superfund program, can undertake cleanup activities and try to recover the costs from the corporate and other polluters. When a federal agency gets on the list, it must come up with cleanup funds out of its budget. `` We have not engaged in budgeteering relating to these cleanups,'' said <PERSON> Jon </PERSON> <PERSON> Cannon </PERSON>, the assistant <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> administrator in charge of the Superfund, when asked about the possible cost to taxpayers. President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s budget request for fiscal 1990 contains $ 500 million for the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> to clean up its hazardous sites. Although little money may be needed during the beginning assessment period, which lasts up to two years, the costs rise once cleanup begins. Cleanup must begin within 15 months after a plan is approved. `` You will see -LRB- budget -RRB- demands ballooning in future years as remedies are selected and the cleanup process, the expensive part of the process, kicks in,'' said Cannon. The <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> intervention is nonetheless important, <PERSON> Cannon </PERSON> said. `` The thing about the proposal is that it sets in motion a process whereby the federal facility is required to reach agreement with <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> for cleanup,'' he said. `` Once the site is listed it becomes a requirement of law that an interagency agreement be achieved, that a schedule be set, that an enforceable program be put in place.'' The proposed additions to the list are followed by a period of public comment, after which they become formal. The 52 sites announced Thursday are in 26 states. <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> had the most sites _ 10 _ followed by <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, each with four. Of the 52 sites, 41 belonged to the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION>, nine to the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, one to the <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and one to the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. So far, 12 of the <ORGANIZATION> DOE </ORGANIZATION>'s 17 nuclear weapons facilities have been proposed for the list or put on it. The Superfund list has 1,224 hazardous waste sites, 889 of which are final and 335 are proposed. Federal sites account for 115 of that total, with 41 final and 74 proposed.
