<FIRST>r i PM-Summit-Site     07-14 0609</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Summit-Site,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>PARIS TODAY: Summit Will be Trial for Latest Architectural Outrage</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Subs for Washington Today</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Summit Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The seven leaders of the world's richest democracies will spend much of the weekend working in a cocoon of marble-covered concrete suspended more than 300 feet in the air. That is, if they do n't mistake the open-air elevator shafts or the tubular artworks adorning the site of the 15th economic summit for scaffolding left behind by the builders. Such is the design of <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Grande </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arche </ORGANIZATION>, a 35-story white marble structure that is one of the French capital's latest architectural outrages. Such is the location for the meetings that run from today through Sunday. In attendance will be President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, French President <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON>, Canadian Prime Minister <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Japanese </LOCATION> Prime Minister Sousuke Uno, West German Chancellor <PERSON> Helmut </PERSON> <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s Prime Minister <PERSON> Ciriaco </PERSON> <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Mita </PERSON>. To imagine the structure, picture a giant white cardboard box standing on its side, with the top and bottom flaps folded in to form what looks like a deep, glassless window frame. The summit strategy sessions on Third World debt, the environment and aid for <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> will be held in the rooftop slab that hangs over a cavernous hollow huge enough to hold the Notre Dame cathedral, including its spire. To reach the summit in the sky, the leaders will ride the bubble elevators that could easily be mistaken for construction staging. Should the statesmen suffer from vertigo, they can ascend to the meetings through a disorienting expanse of stone stairs that stretch 330 feet wide at the cube's base. The Arche is not quite finished, and its inauguration was accelerated to accommodate the prestigious summit. Wittingly or not, the planet's most influential statesmen will serve as the guinea pigs for the controversial new structure, which will eventually house the <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Equipment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> and an array of private companies. Hosting the financial summit in a previously unoccupied building may ease some security chores and avoid disruption of the business activities likely to bustle at the Arche once its trapezoidal towers are replete with as many as 10,000 office workers. But christening the complex with such a high-profile event could also invite embarrassment or disaster. On the eve of the summit, electrical and plumbing problems disabled most of the high-rise's washrooms and elevators proved woefully inadequate for the 4,500 journalists headquartered in the cube. Plastic dropcloths and wooden walkways still obscured much of the courtyard. Walls still needed paint, and electricians worked hurriedly to test the elevators Thursday under the watchful eye of dogs trained to detect explosives. <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> personally chose the design submitted by late Danish architect <PERSON> Johan </PERSON> <PERSON> Otto </PERSON> <PERSON> von </PERSON> <PERSON> Spreckelsen </PERSON> in a 1983 international competition for the structure. The president deemed the cubic entry an effort `` to unite technical prowess with purity of form.'' But in emphasizing form over function, the developers have drawn fire for what many see as more of an oddity than an artistic endeavor. Erected at the western extreme of an imaginary axis extending from the Louvre through the Arc de Triomphe and along the Champs Elysees, the modernistic marble monument completes the La Defense cluster of contemporary office towers that many Parisians consider a wart at the western edge of their revered city. La Defense, a bluff beyond the <LOCATION> Seine </LOCATION> and the Bois de Boulogne where the French held off German aggressors in the 1870 Franco-Prussian war, has raised eyebrows and hackles since the first ultramodern structures took shape in the architectural expressiveness of the 1960s.
</TEXT>
