<FIRST>r w PM-Dial-a-Porn     07-14 0532</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dial-a-Porn,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Votes Phone-Porn Ban, New Communications Fees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A House bill to levy $ 50 million in new and increased licensing fees on many communications businesses would also ban obscene dial-a-porn services and restrict access to indecent phone messages. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> approved the package on Thursday while also voting to enact a new fairness doctrine that requires broadcasters to air opposing views on controversial public issues. The committee action was part of a drive to hold the federal budget deficit in fiscal 1990 to $ 110 billion, as required by the Gramm-Rudman deficit-reduction law. The committee attached the dial-a-porn and fairness doctrine measures to its budget reconciliation bill, which is designed to generate $ 50 million through: _ A 12.6 percent, across-the-board increase in licensing fees charged by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> _ New fees on 17 communications areas previously exempted from charges, including ham radio operators and satellite launching businesses _ Increases in <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> fines that have not been changed since 1934 <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Connolly </PERSON> said the `` vast majority'' of the $ 50 million will come from new fees, with about a third of the money coming from private radio operations such a rural radio, national paging services, offshore radio and mobile and cellular phones. Minimum fees in nearly all cases will be $ 30, as opposed to $ 5 currently. The $ 70,000 for satellites is the maximum. Other fees include a $ 6,760 fee for a telephone company that requests an <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> hearing. The dial-a-porn provision comes in response to a <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling last month that invalidated a 1988 law that had outlawed the $ 2 billion dial-a-porn business. The court said indecent speech was protected by the Constitution but obscene speech was not. The court since 1973 has defined obscenity as a work that is patently offensive, prurient and has no serious literary, artistic, political or scientific value. <PERSON> Connolly </PERSON> said the committee's action `` takes the ruling of the court and works with those constitutional restraints. It bans obscene speech ... and it regulates indecent speech.'' The bill requires telephone companies to block dial-a-porn calls to their customers' lines unless a customer formally asks to have access to the service. The dial-a-porn and licensing fee measures passed on voice votes. But the fairness doctrine was added only after the committee voted 35-8 against an amendment by Rep. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Tauke </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Iowa </LOCATION>, to strip the provision from the bill. <PERSON> Tauke </PERSON> objected that the fairness doctrine, a set of guidelines that were in effect since the 1940s before they were repealed by the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> repealed in 1987, was unnecessary, unconstitutional and made the bill `` veto bait'' at the White House. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> committees both passed fairness doctrine bills in April. President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has indicated he would veto a fairness doctrine law, and fairness doctrine proponents were not assured of enough votes to override a veto. Committee Chairman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON>, D-Mich., who has made the fairness doctrine a top legislative priority this year, adopted the commonly used ploy of attaching a controversial measure to an important spending bill `` The committee feels it's doubtful President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> would veto the entire reconciliation package over fairness,'' <PERSON> Connolly </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
