<SECOND>PM-Forest Deals,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Deals Blow to Companies Cutting Alaskan Forest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'s governor and <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> representative say legislation to cancel sweetheart deals two companies have to cut timber in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'s huge <ORGANIZATION> Tongass </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> is a case of environmentalists going too far. The bill, approved Thursday by a 356-60 vote, would terminate 50-year contracts with the <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> Pacific-Ketchikan and the <ORGANIZATION> Alaska </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pulp </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a Japanese firm, in the southeastern Alaskan forest. Proponents claim the companies have abused their special relationship and stifled competition from other companies while getting trees at bargain-basement prices. Rep. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Calif </LOCATION>., called the timber contracts a `` raid on taxpayers. `` The federal government has spent $ 362 million on Tongass timber subsidies since 1982,'' said <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>. `` But because the government has assessed the value of the trees at rates set in 1956, the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> has received only $ 3.9 million on its $ 362 million investment.'' The size of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> combined, the forest is treasured by environmentalists as a habitat for grizzly bear and bald eagles and contains the largest spawning area for salmon. It's also one of two remaining sections of a rain forest that once extended northward from northern <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and is considered an important protection against global warming. But Alaskan officials say the vote ignored the state's interests. `` Today's House action is an unfortunate case of congressmen from outside <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> voting on the livelihoods of Alaskans,'' Gov. <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Cowper </PERSON> said. `` Alaskans deserve better and I suspect we'll get it when this measure reaches the Senate.'' Republican Rep. <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'s lone representative in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, said the vote demonstrated the power of environmentalists who ignore the need of Alaskans to find jobs. He claims 6,000 jobs would be lost if the lumber companies go out of business. `` I'm terribly disappointed,'' he said. Proponents say competition would be enhanced, however. `` If we cancel these contracts, it does n't drive the timber industry out of <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Mrazek </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, co-sponsor of the bill. `` It simply puts these companies on the same footing as other companies.'' Young, <PERSON> Cowper </PERSON> and many members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, including <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Kika </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> la </PERSON> <PERSON> Garza </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, favor a version that would have called for renegotiation rather than cancellation of the timber contracts. The <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> oversees the <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. But that version was rejected 269-144 on Thursday. <PERSON> Young </PERSON> said if the bill is not changed in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, it will be vetoed by President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. Agriculture Secretary <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON> <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> has already said he would recommend a veto of legislation that called for termination of the contracts. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, whose chairman Rep. <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> <PERSON> Udall </PERSON>, D-Ariz., vowed nine years ago to end the 50-year contracts, is also trying to attach the bill to deficit-reducing legislation which staff members believe would have better chance of becoming law By repealing a $ 40 million annual appropriation that aided the lumber companies, the Tongass Timber Reform Act would save the federal government almost $ 200 million over five years, after subtracting added expenses the bill creates. The legislation also would designate 23 areas as wilderness, barring timber harvesting and development on 1.8 million acres; and ban logging within 100 feet of salmon streams.
</TEXT>
