 Beer ads on television should be regulated so youngsters are not encouraged to drink, an advocacy group says, but the beer industry contends it's up to parents to keep an eye on their kids' viewing habits. The Center for Science in the <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interest </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday that in an informal survey it conducted, television ads for beer were more popular than any other type of commercial among teen-age boys. Forty percent of the high-school boys surveyed said one or more beer ads were their favorites. Of the girls surveyed, 12 percent listed beer and wine ads as their favorites. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Jacobson </PERSON>, executive director of the Washington-based center, said the ads have an impact regardless of beer industry claims that they do n't target youngsters. `` Intentions aside, their advertising is sure reaching these kids, and that's really the issue,'' he said. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanders </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Beer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, said, `` I do n't believe this particular survey reveals anything more than parental neglect. Other surveys have shown no correlation between advertising and increased consumption, <PERSON> Sanders </PERSON> said. The competition within the industry is for a market that has leveled off, he said. <PERSON> Jacobson </PERSON> said the survey showed that advertisements for fast foods and soft drinks as well as beer are popular with teen-agers. `` It's high time that society either restricted such ads or made sure that messages for a more healthful lifestyle reached kids,'' he said. Boys and girls agreed on what made an ad attractive, he said. Those characteristics were humor, rock music and the depiction of athletes or other sports activities. In fact, the single favorite ad among boys was for <ORGANIZATION> Isuzu </ORGANIZATION> cars and trucks, followed by Budweiser or Bud Light. The single favorite among girls was McDonald's, followed by <ORGANIZATION> Pepsi </ORGANIZATION> or Diet Pepsi. The students in the survey were questioned this spring at public and private high schools in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> and rural <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, the Washington-based center said. The 284 responding students listed a total of 1,026 `` favorite or most memorable'' ads. The students' average age was 15.7 years.
