 </PERSON>, <PERSON> Panetta </PERSON> and others on <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> said they expect <ORGANIZATION> OMB </ORGANIZATION> to concede that next year's economy is likely to be less robust than the agency projected in February. A worsening economy tends to increase interest rates the government pays to borrowers and diminish the revenues it collects, driving up the deficit. But the lawmakers said that could be more than compensated for by higher than anticipated revenue collections by the government, as well as some spending savings. <PERSON> Domenici </PERSON> indicated that <ORGANIZATION> OMB </ORGANIZATION> could claim $ 10 billion more in revenue than was expected in February, $ 3 billion in savings from the way the savings and loan industry bailout is being handled, and perhaps $ 1 billion in savings from changes in defense spending. <ORGANIZATION> OMB </ORGANIZATION> officials would n't comment on the forecast. In other budget action Thursday: _ The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> imposed <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> fees on amateur radio operators, nationwide paging services and other radio frequency users, raising an estimated $ 50 million The panel also wrote new restrictions on dial-a-porn companies, and voted to write the Fairness Doctrine into law. The doctrine, enforced by the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> until 1987, requires broadcasters to grant equal time to all sides of issues. _ The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> took credit for saving $ 187 million by renewing the government's flood-insurance program The program is to expire Sept. 30, which would leave about 2 million policyholders eligible to receive benefits but not required to pay premiums. _ The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Governmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> approved legislation moving the money-losing <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> `` off-budget,'' and changing the way the service pays health benefits to families of former employees, pensions and other retirement payments The package claims $ 2.9 billion in savings. _ The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Veterans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> extended a fee it charges for loans and retained restrictions on the loan portfolios it sells, claiming a savings of $ 665 million The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Veterans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> took similar action that it said saved $ 697 million. <ORGANIZATION> OMB </ORGANIZATION>'s deficit projections assume enactment of savings in the $ 1.17 trillion budget passed by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in May. Congressional committees are beginning work on the spending, revenue and savings bills needed to carry out the deficit reduction envisioned in the budget. The congressional budget planned a deficit of $ 105.4 billion in fiscal 1990. The spending plan reflected an agreement worked out in April between President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and congressional leaders.
