<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> said today it was imposing tougher rules on what books and magazines can publish, and there were reports of more executions and prison terms in a continuation of the government's drive to stifle popular dissent A foreign source in <LOCATION> Chengdu </LOCATION>, the capital of central <ORGANIZATION> Sichuan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Province </ORGANIZATION>, quoted local press reports as saying two men were executed last Saturday for their actions during deadly riots in that city in early June. The executions, which were not reported in the national press, brought to 29 the number of people known to have been put to death for disrupting social order since the June 3-4 military assault on <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> in which at least 200 people were killed. Meanwhile, the official <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> said today that the state <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> has decided to take tough new measures to weed out publications it considers unsavory. It said publishers in recent years have `` flooded the book market with low grade and vulgar material which contain violent murders and obscene pornography which have corrupted people's souls.'' It added that books and periodicals to be investigated and removed from bookstalls include those with `` counterrevolutionary and bourgeois liberalization propaganda.'' The Chinese government has blamed the June violence on `` counterrevolutionary rebels'' trying to overthrow the socialist system and has detained or issued arrest warrants for dozens of students and intellectuals who led the pro-democracy movement. Books by scholars now on nationwide wanted lists have been banned, and <ORGANIZATION> Culture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> workers have raided private bookstalls to seize copies. The administration said any bookseller or publisher who violates the regulations will be fined at least five times the profit made. The <LOCATION> Chengdu </LOCATION> source said the two executed men, <PERSON> Zhou </PERSON> <PERSON> Xiangcheng </PERSON> and <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> <PERSON> Guiyuan </PERSON>, were charged with `` beating, smashing, looting and burning,'' a catchall of crimes that <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> uses for rioting. Neither was a student, he said. The <LOCATION> Chengdu </LOCATION> riots of June 4-5 are believed to be the most violent that occurred outside the capital. Up to 30 people were killed as people battled police, and a half-block of the city was destroyed by fire. More than 100 people were later arrested. The source said <LOCATION> Chengdu </LOCATION> courts also gave another man a death sentence with a two-year reprieve and sentenced three others to life imprisonment, one for arson and two for `` hooliganism.'' The two-year stay of execution means the sentence is converted to life if the prisoner shows a proper attitude. The source said courts in <LOCATION> Chengdu </LOCATION> the past week have sentenced 20 others to prison terms ranging from five years to life. In the first weeks following the violence in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s national media reported the arrests of more than 2,000 people who took part in protests The arrests still are believed to be going on, although the national press rarely reports them now. One exception was Thursday, when television news showed an office worker being given a 10-year prison term for spreading rumors during an interview with <ORGANIZATION> ABC-TV </ORGANIZATION>. The interview, in which <PERSON> Xiao </PERSON> <PERSON> Bin </PERSON>, 42, of <LOCATION> Dalian </LOCATION> told <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> that 20,000 people were killed by troops during their attack on Tiananmen Square, apparently was intercepted by <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> when <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> was sending the unedited tape by satellite. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> TV broadcast the tape and demanded that people turn the man in. Two women reported <PERSON> Xiao </PERSON> to police and later received cash rewards. <ORGANIZATION> Xinjiang </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION>, in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s westernmost province, also reported Thursday that 10 people had received prison terms ranging from one year to life for involvement in a May 19 riot in the provincial capital of <LOCATION> Urumqi </LOCATION>. One man received life imprisonment for `` a serious case of beating, smashing and looting'' during the riot when, according to official accounts, 150 policemen and government officials were injured, 20 of them seriously, and 43 trucks were overturned. The <LOCATION> Urumqi </LOCATION> disturbances focused on protests over a Chinese-language book, `` Sexual Customs,'' which Moslems claimed insulted their religion. About half of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s 15 million Moslems live in <LOCATION> Xinjiang </LOCATION>.
