 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar rose today against the Japanese yen in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> while prices on the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> fell for the third consecutive day. The dollar ended the week at 139.50 yen, up 0.45 yen from Thursday's close of 139.05 yen. After opening higher at 139.60 yen, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency ranged between 139.35 and 139.68 yen. The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which lost 70.36 points Thursday, shed another 56.39 points, or 0.16 percent, closing the week at 33,574.77. The index lost 45.25 points on Wednesday. <PERSON> Shinya </PERSON> <PERSON> Hirota </PERSON>, a dealer with the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION>, described the day's currency trading as `` very quiet'' because many market players were staying on the sidelines prior to the release of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic indicators in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> later today. The statistics include the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> producer price index for June and industrial production and retail sales figures, which are regarded as important indicators of the state of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy. <PERSON> Hiromichi </PERSON> <PERSON> Ishikawa </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Yamaichi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION>, a major Japanese brokerage, said trading on the stock market also was very thin, with many participants also awaiting the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic figures. Volume on the market's first section was estimated at 330 million shares, down from 550 million shares on Thursday. Contributing to the decline in the Nikkei index was investor concern over continuing political uncertainty in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Ishikawa </PERSON> said. Political analysts predict the governing <ORGANIZATION> Liberal 