<SECOND>PM-Obit-Hook,0408</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sidney Hook, Philosopher, Author, Educator, Dead at 86</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STANFORD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Philosopher <PERSON> Sidney </PERSON> <PERSON> Hook </PERSON>, a prolific writer whose 1943 work `` The Hero in History'' is still used as a college text, has died of congestive heart failure. He was 86. Hook, a leading figure in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> intellectual circles since the late'20s, died at <ORGANIZATION> Stanford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday. He had been a senior research fellow at the <ORGANIZATION> Hoover </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institution </ORGANIZATION> on War, Revolution and Peace on the <LOCATION> Stanford </LOCATION> campus since 1973. His major books include `` The Metaphysics of Pragmatism,'' published in 1927; `` Towards the Understanding of <PERSON> Karl </PERSON> <PERSON> Marx </PERSON>,'' 1933; `` From <PERSON> Hegel </PERSON> to Marx: Studies in the Intellectual Development of <PERSON> Karl </PERSON> <PERSON> Marx </PERSON>,'' 1936; and `` Common Sense and the Fifth Amendment,'' published in 1957. Hook's best-known work, `` The Hero in History,'' won the prestigious <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Murray </PERSON> <PERSON> Butler </PERSON> Silver Medal of distinction in philosophy and education. Of all his writings, the one that received the most mail was an essay in The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> in 1987 called `` In Defense of Voluntary Euthanasia.'' `` I shall not be sorry to leave this world,'' <PERSON> Hook </PERSON> wrote. `` I've had a happy life I'm one of the lucky people who can live in their work, instead of after work.'' He wrote in his 1987 autobiography, `` Out of Step: An Unquiet Life in The 20th Century,'' that his key belief was that the central problem of the modern era is `` the defense and enrichment of a free and open society against totalitarianism.'' Hook founded in 1951 the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Freedom </ORGANIZATION> and was an early critic of Sen. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON>, who charged that communists had infiltrated the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government. Hook expounded his views on issues of that era in two books, one titled, `` Heresy, Yes _ Conspiracy, No!'' He took the <ORGANIZATION> Stanford </ORGANIZATION> position in 1973 after he retired from <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, where he had taught since 1927 and served as chairman of the philosophy department until 1968. Hook became a leading proponent of philosopher <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Dewey </PERSON>'s ideals, known as pragmatism, a peculiarly American philosophy that an idea must be judged by how it works `` The Metaphysics of Pragmatism,'' his first book, was an exposition of <PERSON> Dewey </PERSON>'s thought. At the time of his death, <PERSON> Hook </PERSON> was planning a retrospective essay on <PERSON> Dewey </PERSON>, who died in 1952, that was intended for publication in the final volume of <PERSON> Dewey </PERSON>'s `` Collected Works.''
</TEXT>
