<HEAD>Consumer Group Seeks Chemical Tests on U.S. Cherries, Other Imports</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with lab report, ministry comment.
Picks up graf 8 pvs, `Song said ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A consumer group said today that it planned to test <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> cherries and other agricultural imports to determine if they contain unsafe levels of pesticides or carcinogens. The <ORGANIZATION> Citizens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Consumer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Korea </ORGANIZATION> said the tests would be conducted in overseas laboratories if South Korean labs either can not or will not cooperate. The first tests will be performed on imported <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> cherries to determine if they contain the chemical daminozide, or Alar, a suspected cancer-causing agent. Other imported <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> agricultural products also will be tested, said <PERSON> Song </PERSON> <PERSON> Bo-kyung </PERSON>, vice president of the alliance. Meanwhile, the <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> said today that recent concerns over food safety would result in more detailed testing of all imported food products. The ministry said laboratory testing on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> imported grapefruits and oranges showed they contained no Alar, but it said tests would be conducted on other agricultural products such as apple juice. The alliance recently led a nationwide boycott of <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> grapefruit after it said a government lab report indicated the presence of Alar on some fruit. Although the lab later clarified the report to say that its test did not find the chemical, consumers remained skeptical. The government lab declined to retest the grapefruit and an independent lab said it did not have the equipment. Meanwhile, <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>'s consumer movement against all chemicals in food production has grown. On Thursday, the Agriculture, <ORGANIZATION> Forestry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fisheries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> announced a ban on the sale and use of Alar on Korean farm products. Last year, an estimated 12,540 pounds of Alar was sold to South Korean farmers, the ministry said. Song said the concern is not restricted to Alar, which is used to enhance color and perserve storage life. `` The other issue is residues of pesticides and chemicals on all imported food commodities _ from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> or anywhere else.'' She said this included beef products as well as fruits and vegetables. Song said that Korean consumer groups depend heavily on consumer groups in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> for research and information and the alliance coordinates with groups in other parts of the world. `` We are concerned about the safety of foods the consumers eat,'' she said. `` We are not concerned for the businessmen or trade issues.'' <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> has pushed <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> to open its markets to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> agricultural products to help correct <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>'s trade imbalance, which was $ 8.5 billion in 1988. South Korean farmers have staged protests against <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> products claiming they undercut domestic prices. The citizen's alliance is one of the largest and most outspoken of 10 leading consumer associations that claim a combined nationwide membership of 2 million.
