<TEXT>
 Health authorities have confirmed an outbreak of typhoid fever among visitors to a <LOCATION> Catskill </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountain </LOCATION> resort town last month, with 13 cases identified and another 20 suspected. The victims include people who attended a convention of the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chiefs </ORGANIZATION> at the <LOCATION> Pines </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hotel </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Fallsburg </LOCATION>, about 90 miles northwest of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Faith </PERSON> <PERSON> Schottenfeld </PERSON> said Thursday. In addition to several conventioneers, a hotel restaurant worker and two members of a senior citizens group that stayed at the hotel at the time have contracted the disease, <PERSON> Schottenfeld </PERSON> said. More than 10,000 New Yorkers attended the convention June 12 and 13. Thousands of other tourists who had stayed in the area are being questioned in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Schottenfeld </PERSON> said. The disease has been identified in residents of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION> so far, she said. Visitors to the resort should be showing symptoms of typhoid fever by now if they have the disease, she added. The number of confirmed cases has grown since the <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> first reported four cases on Tuesday. Typhoid is spread by eating or drinking food and water contaminated by people carrying the infection. The bacteria is shed in the feces of carriers. Symptoms usually appear one to three weeks after exposure and include fever, headache and diarrhea or constipation. Typhoid is easily treated with antibiotics and victims usually recover within a week.
