 A state <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> caseworker has been charged with failing to report a suspected case of sexual abuse after an 8-year-old boy in a foster home died of AIDS. The indictment issued Thursday by a <LOCATION> Richland </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> grand jury charged <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Edson </PERSON> with not investigating the case or notifying the proper law enforcement authorities as required by law. The foster mother of <PERSON> Brett </PERSON> <PERSON> Hall </PERSON>, of <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>, told <PERSON> Edson </PERSON> in October 1987 that the boy had been sexually abused, but <PERSON> Edson </PERSON> waited eight months before beginning his investigation, according to the indictment. By that time <PERSON> Brett </PERSON> was dying of acquired immune deficiency syndrome, a breakdown of the body's immune system which leaves the victim fatally susceptible to viruses. <PERSON> Brett </PERSON> was 9 when he died in November. <PERSON> Edson </PERSON> was indicted on two counts of obstruction of justice and two counts of failure to report child abuse. A 1977 state law requires child protection agencies to follow through on any suspected case of child abuse or neglect within 24 hours. Each count of obstruction of justice carries a maximum 10-year prison term. Each count of failure to report child abuse carries a maximum 6-month prison term and $ 500 fine. Social Services spokeswoman <PERSON> Norma </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>, who has worked at the agency since 1973, said it was the first time in her memory that an employee has been indicted on criminal charges for failing to follow through on a suspected child abuse case. <PERSON> Edson </PERSON> declined to comment on the indictment, <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> newspaper reported today. Calls by The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> to his home this morning were not immediately returned. State policy requires employees who have been indicted to be suspended or transferred to a less sensitive position until the criminal charges are resolved. No action had been taken Thursday on <PERSON> Edson </PERSON>. Now that <PERSON> Brett </PERSON> is dead, there is no way to prosecute the person responsible, so the investigation has turned toward the boy's caseworker, said <PERSON> Julaan </PERSON> <PERSON> Prince </PERSON>, an assistant solicitor in <LOCATION> Conway </LOCATION>
