<SECOND>PM-Factory Use,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Factory Utilization and Production Both Fell in June</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The operating rate for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> factories fell in June to 83.5 percent, while industrial production dropped 0.2 percent, the government said today, further easing concerns about inflation but providing more evidence of a slowing economy. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> said the June operating rate declined 0.3 percentage point from May's 83.8 percent and April's 84.1 percent. The rate hit a 10-year high of 84.3 percent last December. `` Declines were widespread throughout the industrial sector, with especially large drops for autos, mining and utilities,'' the central bank said. Economists had worried that the steady upward march of operating rates last year signaled increased inflationary pressures. The closer <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> industry gets to full operating capacity, the greater difficulty it has producing enough to meet demand, leading to shortages and price increases. Analysts generally consider an operating rate of 85 percent or above as an indication of inflationary pressures. Until recently, the central bank has been pushing up interest rates in an attempt to cool inflationary pressures without slowing growth so much that the economy slides into a recession. In its other report today, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> said its industrial production index stood at 141.1 percent of its 1977 base, 3.4 percent higher than a year ago but down from May's 141.4 percent. It was the first decline since it fell 0.2 percent in February, which had been the first drop in a year. The pace of industrial production had risen 0.6 percent in April. Last month's factory operating rate of 83.5 percent was up from 83.0 percent a year earlier. The operating rate fell 0.3 percentage point to 83.8 percent at manufacturing plants, down from May's 84.1 percent. Prior to April, the rate had declined since it peaked at 84.7 percent in January. The rate at factories producing durable goods, big ticket items expected to last more than three years, fell 0.3 percentage point from 82.7 percent in May, reflecting in large part a reduction in the production of autos. The rate at factories producing non-durable goods dropped to 85.8 percent, comparied to May's 86.0 percent. Production, meanwhile, remained flat at manufacturing plants making both durable and non-durable goods. Output at mines and oil wells fell 1.1 percent following a revised 0.3 percent decline in May. The June output was 1.7 percent lower than a year ago and, analysts said, in part reflected the effects of a month-old wildcat strike by more than 30,000 coal miners in <LOCATION> Appalachia </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>. Production at utilities dropped 1.3 percent in June, due in part to decreased use of air conditioning because of cooler-than-normal weather. Utility production had dropped 0.2 percent in May.
