<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The prominence given to the environment at the <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> economic summit reflects a growing view among world leaders that the battle against pollution is too immense and complicated for a single nation to tackle. President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and his advisers are expected to argue forcefully that unless a resounding effort is made to enlist all countries, the moves to cut pollution by a few nations could be wiped out by actions taken _ or not taken _ elsewhere in the world. So leaders of the seven largest industrial nations _ the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> _ want to conclude their meeting Sunday with a unified voice that will carry weight among leaders not present. The summit participants are aware that the environment has become a hot political issue. Repeated polls indicate that people want their leaders to tackle the world's pollution problems. At the same time, the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration sees the environment as a way for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to extend a new form of leadership in the sometimes troubled Western alliance as well as becoming the conduit toward closer East-West ties in the coming years. `` Our shared heritage is the <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>,'' President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said during his stay in <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>. `` And the fate of the <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION> transcends borders. It is not just an East-West issue.'' Dozens of international conferences have been held or are scheduled for the next few years to deal with global warming, the decay of the protective stratospheric ozone layer, dirty urban air, and oceans contaminated with everything from medical wastes to sprawling oil spills. All of these topics will be the focus of debate at the economic summit today through Sunday in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>. The environment is coming on like `` a freight train'' as an international issue, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has said. His chief environmental spokesman, <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Reilly </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, complained recently that some of the conference participants may be trying to move too quickly. `` There is something of a race on by some of the economic summit participants ... to be the greenest of all on this issue,'' said <PERSON> Reilly </PERSON>, the first <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> administrator ever to attend an economic summit. `` Restoring the environment is not a sprinter's game; it's going to require steady, long-term commitments. The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration, however, has been criticized by some environmentalists for being too slow in asserting <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> leadership on dealing with the growing global environmental mess. Earlier this year the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> dragged behind in calling for a ban on the production of chlorofluorocarbons, or CFCs, which are blamed for depleting the ozone layer. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> announced support for a ban only after European nations did. The administration also waited until the last minute before calling for an international workshop on global warming and then did so after critics charged the president was backing away from a campaign pledge to host such a conference. The workshop was to be held in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, but now is planned for <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> in October, although <PERSON> Reilly </PERSON> insists the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will remain its `` host.'' The seven nations at the summit use about 60 percent of the world's ozone-depleting CFCs and account for about 40 percent of the world's carbon dioxide emissions from the burning of fossil fuels, the principal culprit in global warming. `` You would n't launch a Marshall Plan at an economic summit,'' <PERSON> Reilly </PERSON> quipped to reporters recently while reviewing his expectations of the <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> meeting, the 15th such summit and the first in which the environment has held this much attention.
