<HEAD>Hamlet Has Party, Fireworks, But Where's The Band?</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-France-Bicentennial, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAF CASERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. GENGOUX DE SCISSE, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Just like <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, this hamlet deep in wine-growing Burgundy went out of its way to make its bicentennial celebration an unparalleled event. Unlike Parisians, however, the 548 villagers could get a close look at the fireworks display, the first ever in the history of St. Gengoux. They also had no trouble parking and did n't complain about the cost of it all. That does n't mean the festivities were a cinch for mayor <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Pelletier </PERSON>. `` We had worries to organize this,'' he said. `` For the official toast, we had to get our hands on 200 glasses and think who would do the washing up afterward.'' With all eyes glued on <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> where world leaders marked the 200th anniversary of the French Revolution in pomp, splendor and grandeur, hundreds of villages around <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> celebrated with a simple `` bal populaire,'' and heaps of food and wine. On the eve of Bastille Day, the children of <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gengoux </PERSON> marched around the village carrying colorful lanterns. The elders, dressed in period costumes, followed and chanted revolutionary slogans such as `` That's enough. We'll hang the aristocracy!'' and `` Down with the nobility and clergy!'' when they passed the 11th century church. But times have changed. <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gengoux </PERSON> no longer has a resident priest, the sole policeman did not have to protect anyone from the outrage of the people, and by 3:30 a.m. the locals were swaying to `` Rock Around the Clock'' by <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Haley </PERSON> and the Comets. One thing was missing, though. For the first time in memory, the brass band, rich in trophies and local history, did not lead the procession. After the previous mayor lost the March elections, his son and cousin quit the band, taking with them their bugle and big drum. `` What a pity we had to miss that,'' said <PERSON> Pelletier </PERSON>, echoing the complaints of many villagers. But it hardly dampened the enthusiasm during the simple festivities. `` Here, everything is very down to earth,'' said baker <PERSON> Jeannot </PERSON> <PERSON> Breton </PERSON>. `` We celebrate among ourselves. We do n't have an orgy of money,'' he said. The mayor runs the July 14 celebrations on a budget of less than $ 1,500. `` Of course, we do n't have to receive heads of state,'' he said. <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gengoux </PERSON>, basking amid the lush, sloping hills of eastern <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, produces simple <LOCATION> Macon </LOCATION> white wines from Chardonnay grapes, but without the fame or prices of the Burgundy wines from around <LOCATION> Beaune </LOCATION>, 40 miles to the north. Friday's celebrations ended with the bicentennial `` <PERSON> Repas </PERSON> <PERSON> Populaire </PERSON>,'' a rich five-course meal for about $ 7.50 a plate, but with wine and coffee offered by the village. More than 200 people showed up in the <LOCATION> Salle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> des </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Fetes </LOCATION>, decorated in the French colors for the occasion. During the two days, only one big speech was made, but even then it hardly resembled the heady rhetoric heard in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, where the Revolution was lauded as one of <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>'s greatest contributions to humanity. The people here have their ideas what 1789 means. In <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gengoux </LOCATION>, there were attacks during the revolutionary summer to destroy everything that represented the nobility and clergy but no major massacres occured. `` Like everywhere, July 14 means liberty. We have maintained it and even abused it a lot,'' <PERSON> Breton </PERSON> said, referring to <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>'s colonial past `` When something is forbidden, we are the first to do it,'' he said. The quest for an egalitarian society however has partly failed, said <PERSON> Pelletier </PERSON>. `` The differences are still there, but they are not so big as 200 years ago,'' he said. `` Some privileges have survived,'' he said. <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gengoux </PERSON> will continue to celebrate until the end of July to commemorate events in the region itself. `` On July 14, nothing happened here,'' said <PERSON> Pelletier </PERSON>. `` There was no television to see live how the Bastille was taken.''
