<HEAD>Cardinal Appeals For End of Persecution in China</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BIERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Roman Catholic bishop of <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> has appealed for international pressure on <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> to offer refuge to the territory's people as a safeguard from the uncertain future under communist rule. Cardinal <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wu </PERSON>, in a letter to about 2,500 cardinals and bishops seen Friday, also urged pressure on <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> to end persecution of participants in the crushed pro-democracy movement. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> has agreed to return <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> in 1997, and <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> has promised that the territory can maintain its capitalist economy and enjoy a `` high degree of autonomy'' for another 50 years. But the June 3-4 military suppression of the pro-democracy movement in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> and subsequent crackdown on dissent throughout <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> has led to a loss of confidence in the future among the 5.7 million people of <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>. `` These events have shaken not just <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, but the entire world,'' <PERSON> Wu </PERSON> said. `` <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> has felt particularly deeply the sufferings of its Chinese brothers and sisters.'' <PERSON> Wu </PERSON> argued that recent events in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> have increased anxieties in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, and he said <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> had a constitutional and moral obligation to provide safeguards for the territory's people. `` A right to enter the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kingdom </LOCATION> would, in no small measure, help restore people's confidence in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>,'' he said, echoing arguments made by many of the colony's public opinion le