<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Chinese censors have pledged to expunge unacceptable political works from bookstores, official reports said Friday, and prosecutors said they will continue to punish dissidents `` without mercy.'' <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> officials also warned that more than a month after the bloody military demolition of the student-led pro-democracy movement that `` counterrevolutionary'' resistance persists, and the capture of rebels is crucial to the survival of the state. Two more protesters were executed in southwestern city of <LOCATION> Chengdu </LOCATION>, a foreign source in the <LOCATION> Sichuan </LOCATION> provincial capital said Friday, bringing to 29 the known number put to death for actions during the past month of social unrest. The <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> and Publications Administrations has taken new measures to clean up the publishing industry, the official <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> reported It said there will be tighter surveillance of pornographic material and a sweep against `` counterrevolutionary and bourgeois liberalization propaganda.'' Already, Culture Ministry workers have raided bookstalls to remove works by scholars wanted by police for advocating democratic reform before the June 3-4 military assault crushed the pro-democracy movement and solidified power for senior leader <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> <PERSON> Xiaoping </PERSON> and other aging ideologues. Before then, writers enjoyed a period of relative freedom of expression, and publishers sought profits from adventure stories and romances, some of dubious taste, popular among the general public. It said censors in the past had not been strict enough and publishing companies `` pursuing economic results gave up principle and flooded the book market with low-grade and vulgar materials which contain violent murders and obscene pornography which have corrupted people's souls.'' The Beijing Daily quoted <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Qiyan </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> deputy secretary for <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>, as saying organizers of the `` counterrevolutionary rebellion'' still are at large and `` their capture is of vital importance to the survival of the party, the stability of the society and the fundamental interest of the people.'' He said the counterrevolutionaries, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s term for leaders of the democracy movement, `` are so arrogant that they are still distributing anti-revolutionary rumor, resorting to demagoguery ... and putting up a vain resistance.'' At the same meeting of senior <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> officials, municipal party chief <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Ximing </PERSON> said supporters of `` bourgeois liberalization,'' of Western ideas and culture, `` will never accept their defeat ... but use every method to spoil our most important work.'' In a separate report from the official <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, senior prosecutor <PERSON> Feng </PERSON> <PERSON> Jinwen </PERSON> said all those who violated the law during the recent unrest will be punished `` without mercy.'' Feng called for speedy trials and harsh verdicts for such crimes as organizing and planning riots and rebellion in collaboration with reactionary forces at home and abroad in an attempt to overthrow the socialist system, inciting people to riot with counterrevolutionary slogans, beating and killing troops, destroying or setting fire to military vehicles and seizing weapons. In <LOCATION> Chengdu </LOCATION>, two men were executed July 8 for `` beating, smashing, looting and burning'' _ a catchall of crimes <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> uses for rioting, a foreign source said Friday, quoting local press reports. The source said the <LOCATION> Chengdu </LOCATION> court sentenced another man to death with a two-year stay of execution and gave life sentences to three others, one for arson and two for `` hooliganism.'' <LOCATION> Chengdu </LOCATION> courts in the past week have sentenced 20 others to prison terms ranging from five years to life, he said. Up to 30 people were killed in clashes between police and rioters in <LOCATION> Chengdu </LOCATION> on June 4 and 5. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> says about 200 civilians were killed in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. Chinese sources and Western diplomats say thousands were slain. Meanwhile, officials continued a concerted campaign to convince foreign tourists and businessmen they should return to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. The capital on Friday opened an international trade fair with exhibits from 24 countries, and <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> said the `` festive and friendly atmosphere at the fair did not seem to be affected by the martial law still going on in the city.''
