<HEAD>Eight Civilians and Troops Killed in Shooting Outside Somali Mosque</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Troops opened fire Friday on worshipers outside a mosque in <LOCATION> Mogadishu </LOCATION>, the Somali capital, and state radio reported eight people were killed in what the government called religious disturbances. A resident said it appeared troops opened fire as Moslems left their place of prayer during <PERSON> Eid </PERSON> <PERSON> al-Adha </PERSON>, the three-day Feast of Sacrifice that is Islam's holiest celebration. The resident, who spoke on condition he not be identified further, said gunfire erupted around midday and continued sporadically through the afternoon. He said most of the shooting appeared to be around a mosque in a western neighborhood. The shootings come in a week of unconfirmed reports that authorities have detained several Moslem religious leaders. A Ministry of the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> statement broadcast on state radio said a group of `` troublemakers masquerading behind the cloak of religion'' started the disturbances in <LOCATION> Hodhan </LOCATION> neighborhood. The report, monitored in <LOCATION> Nairobi </LOCATION>, said security forces were called out to curb the disturbances but the `` troublemakers refused to disperse peacefully.'' Fighting broke out and eight people were killed and 24 were injured, according to the statement. The dead included `` troublemakers'' and members of the security forces, it said. The resident said the government imposed a 6 p.m. to 6 a.m. curfew in the capital. He said he saw little activity during an afternoon drive through <LOCATION> Mogadishu </LOCATION>, except for two soldiers guarding an army post. `` However, people in the neighborhood say they've heard gunfire all around,'' he said. On Sunday, an unidentified gunman shot and killed <PERSON> Mogadishu </PERSON>'s Roman Catholic Bishop <PERSON> Salvatore </PERSON> <PERSON> Pietro </PERSON> <PERSON> Colombo </PERSON> It was not known whether Friday's disturbances were related. This East African nation on the <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION> has been led since 1969 by the autocratic President <PERSON> Siad </PERSON> <PERSON> Barre </PERSON>, who allows no opposition to his rule. It is difficult to get news from the country. Since 1981, the government has battled the <ORGANIZATION> Somali </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION>, a northern insurgency that demands <PERSON> Barre </PERSON>'s removal. Intensified fighting between the rebels and the government the past 18 months has driven more than 200,000 Somalis into refugee camps in neighboring <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>. The impoverished nation is overwhelmingly pastoral and most of the 9 million people are Moslem.
