<HEAD>Auto and Home Furnishing Purchases Drag Down Retail Sales</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Retail sales fell 0.4 percent in June, dragged down by falling auto and home furnishing purchases, the government reported Friday, and analysts said big-ticket items would continue to bear the brunt of the anti-inflation fight. `` The decline in sales reflects that people are getting a little cautious about spending their money,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Wyss </PERSON>, senior financial economist for <ORGANIZATION> DRI </ORGANIZATION> @ <ORGANIZATION> McGraw-Hill </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Lexington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, economic forecasting organization. `` That's partially because there's been a lot of talk about the risk of recession and people are taking that seriously,'' he explained. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dederick </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Northern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, agreed, saying: `` The pocketbook has n't been zipped up completely, but it's closed to a considerable degree. <PERSON> Rosalind </PERSON> <PERSON> Wells </PERSON>, chief economist for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Retail </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Merchants </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, noted the sales decline was concentrated in the durable goods area and predicted the pattern would continue for the remainder of the year because of high interest rates. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> reported that sales fell to a seasonally adjusted $ 140.8 billion last month after dropping 0.1 percent in May. It was the first back-to-back monthly decline since 1987 when sales declined 0.8 percent in September and 0.9 percent in October. Retail spending is watched closly as a measure of the overall economy since it accounts for about a third of economic activity. Car sales, which represent about 20 percent of total retail sales, led the overall decline last month. They fell 2.0 percent, following a 1.8 percent drop in May. It was the steepest fall since a 4.0 percent decline in October 1987. However, <PERSON> Dederick </PERSON> and <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Evans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> said auto sales have picked up since the June survey was taken. Some analysts said the latest retail sales report would provide the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> additional incentive to lower interest rates as it seeks a `` soft-landing,'' rather than drive the economy into a recession as it fights inflation. `` It's not a question of whether the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> will ease further,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, an economist for <ORGANIZATION> Aubrey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> G. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lanston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` It's only a matter of when.'' Until recently, interest rates have risen as the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> tightened its grip on credit to slow the economy and stem inflation. While rates have begun to fall, they are still high enough to affect spending on durable goods _ big-ticket items expected to last more than three years. Durable goods sales were off 1.3 percent in June after falling 0.5 percent in May, <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> said. Besides autos, sales of furniture and other home furnishings were off 0.1 percent. Sales of non-durable goods rose 0.2 percent, including a 2.1 percent increase in department store and other general merchandise spending and a 1.9 percent hike in clothing sales. `` The one shining light will continue to be apparel,'' particularly women's clothing, said Ms. <PERSON> Wells </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Retail </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Merchants </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. `` It's the only area where there's pent-up demand,'' she said, following several years when women postponed purchases `` because they did n't like the style or whatever.'' Non-durable categories posting sales declines included food stores, down 0.7 percent; gasoline stations, down 0.5 percent; restaurants and bars, down 0.2 percent and drug stores, off 0.3 percent. Retail sales were up 5.3 percent from April through June, compared with the same period in 1988.
