<HEAD>Rival Moslems Clash over Water and Land; One Killed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Rival Moslem sects in the Central Asian republic of <LOCATION> Tadzhikistan </LOCATION> fought over water and land rights, and one person was killed and 18 were wounded, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> reported Friday. Thousands of people, some with guns, clashed Thursday night between the villages of <LOCATION> Vorukh </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Chorku </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> Isfara </LOCATION> region, the traditional site of rivalries between Iranian-speaking and Turkic-speaking Moslems. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION>, the official Soviet news agency, said <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> first secretaries of the neighboring republics of <LOCATION> Kirghizia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Tadzhikistan </LOCATION> rushed to the scene to calm things down. Elsewhere in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, ethnic tension continued to run high in <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> Caucasus </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountains </LOCATION>, according to reports reaching <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. The violence continued as preparations continued for a <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> meeting in late July on nationality problems that have erupted under the liberalizing reforms of President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. Authorities have not announced a date for the plenum. The latest violence in <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> stems from an old dispute about land and water use at <LOCATION> Isfara </LOCATION>, in <LOCATION> Leninabad </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Oblast </LOCATION> on the border between <LOCATION> Kirghizia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Tadzhikistan </LOCATION>. The border near the disputed area is jagged as authorities gerrymandered along ethnic lines when they carved the republics from the former Tsarist province of Turkestan in the 1920s. Cooperative use of an irrigation canal at <LOCATION> Isfara </LOCATION> ended at the beginning of this year when the disputing parties filled it with stones, `` causing substantial agricultural losses,'' <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> reported. The situation worsened the last three months as local authorities decided to build additional settlements in the area `` without undertaking the necessary consultations with residents'' on water and energy supplies, it said. In <LOCATION> Stepanakert </LOCATION>, capital of the <ORGANIZATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Autonomous </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Region </ORGANIZATION>, Armenian residents circulated a photograph of an Armenian watchman killed at a livestock complex Wednesday night in the nearby town of Shush, said a worker at the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> there. `` His throat was slit and his eyes were cut out,'' said the worker, an Armenian who declined to identify himself. Demonstrations began nearly two years ago in <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> and the neighboring republic of <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> to protest the administration of the enclave by the <LOCATION> Azerbaijani </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> lies within <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>, a predominately Moslem republic, but the majority are Armenian Christians. No one has been arrested for the most recent murder, although investigators have been sent to the region and <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> troops have been patrolling all week, according to official reports. In the nearby republic of <LOCATIO