<FIRST>r a AM-Kids'Guides     07-14 0613</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kids' Guides,0632</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Kids' Guides' Help Kids Cope With Hospitals, Being Alone</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUDIE GLAVE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 You are 5 years old. You are in the hospital and about to have surgery for bronchial complications when the child in the next bed offers this advice: `` Do n't cough during surgery or you'll die.'' It happened to <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Banks </PERSON> 30 years ago, and the memory of that moment lingered and sparked the first in a series of books aimed at helping kids 8 to 12 years old cope with uncomfortable situations. The books, `` Hospital Journal: A Kid's Guide to a Strange Place'' and `` Alone at Home: A Kid's Guide to Being in Charge,'' were published in June by Viking Penguin. `` There are plenty of story books already out on both of these situations, but sometimes telling a story just is n't enough, or it's too much,'' the author said in a recent interview Banks uses a workbook format which allows children to `` write things down, learn about them, and hopefully, gain control of the situation.'' Each year, she says, about 4 million children enter the hospital for an overnight stay. For many, it is their first hospital visit. Banks recalled that at age 5, she did n't know whether to believe her roommate's startling claim about the danger of coughing. `` But I sure remember being too afraid to ask anyone,'' she said. As a result, the hospital book includes a page titled `` Will It Hurt?'' and urges readers to ask their doctors and parents to describe exactly what will happen to them before, during and after surgery. The bood also includes sections on getting to know doctors and nurses, where children ask their medical people about their favorite television shows, their hobbies, and about why they chose their profession. `` This way they learn something personal about these people and hopefully feel more at ease around them,'' <PERSON> Banks </PERSON> said. Banks talked to scores of teen-agers, doctors, nurses, guidance counselors and specialists. A section of the hospital book dealing with privacy -LRB- or, more accurately, the lack of it -RRB- grew from the interviews with teens. `` The kids talked a lot about how embarrassing it was when the nurse did n't close the curtain enough, or they had to be helped onto a bedpan ... the minute I heard it, I knew it was important to them.'' The result is a section called `` This is Embarrassing!'' which urges kids to talk about those indelicate times. Youngsters are encouraged to count the injections they receive; to ask new people they meet to autograph the book; to laugh at hospital jokes -LRB- `` What do you call a sick alligator? An illigator.'' -RRB- The second book, `` Alone at Home,'' asks children to list the locations of first-aid supplies; the phone numbers of working parents; and `` special people,'' neighbors who a child can turn to if problems arise. With more women working full-time, some experts estimate there are 6 million so-called latchkey kids who come home from school daily to empty houses. `` You tell a child you'll be home a certain time and then stop off at the grocery store or run some other errand that makes you 15 minutes late; those few extra minutes can seem like a very long time for a kid.'' Each book concludes with a parents' guide. Parents are asked to work with their kids in completing the workbooks _ rehearsing what they should do if they lose their keys, or if someone knocks at the door. Banks, who lives in <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> and is the mother of 5-year-old <PERSON> Kate </PERSON>, plans two more books for the series _ one on divorce and the other on living in stepfamilies.
</TEXT>
