<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasters </ORGANIZATION> on Friday applauded a <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> decision allowing small FM stations to double their signals and reach larger audiences. NAB President <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> O. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fritts </PERSON> said the group `` strongly endorsed'' Thursday's <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> decision to allow many so-called Class A FM stations to boost their power from 3,000 watts to 6,000 watts. About 500 of the nation's 2,000 Class A FM stations, most of which serve small communities, could make the switch as early as Dec. 1 without causing interference problems for other stations. Another 800 or so stations will be able to apply for permission to change tower locations or to resolve other technical problems preventing an immediate power boost, <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said Friday. The remaining stations wo n't be able to change. `` We're very pleased that the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> authorized the doubling of power to many FM operations,'' <PERSON> Fritts </PERSON> said. `` Secondly, the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> wisely recognized that general, across-the-board increases could do serious harm to the integrity of the FM spectrum. The commission's case-by-case consideration of additional power increase applications may alleviate any other interference problems that may be presented.'' The commission said the increased power would allow the stations to provide better service to their listeners. The commission also revised the distances by which Class A stations must be separated from other stations to limit interference. The current separation is 105 kilometers, or about 65 miles, while the new separation will be 115 kilometers, or about 71 miles, effective Oct. 2. `` The area covered will be 40 percent greater,'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said. Class A FM stations are the most numerous of the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION>'s seven classes of FM stations and those that have the smallest service areas. The largest FM stations have signals with 100,000 watts or more. The commission said the small communities to which Class A channels were originally allotted have grown, while the coverage of these stations has remained unchanged. <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> said he feared the new rule would exacerbate the commission's already backlogged application process, adding that he hoped <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> would allocate additional funds to the agency to handle the expected glut.
