<HEAD>Factory Operating, Industrial Production Down</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Both the factory operating rate and industrial production fell last month, the government said Friday, providing more evidence of a slowing economy caused by anti-inflation measures. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> said the June operating rate declined to 83.5 percent, a 0.3 percentage point drop from May. The rate was 84.1 percent in April and hit a 10-year high of 84.3 percent in December. The <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> also said industrial production was off 0.2 percent last month, with its industrial production index standing at 141.1 percent of its 1977 base, down from May's 141.4 percent. It was the first decline since it fell 0.2 percent in February, which had been the first drop in a year. `` It's really related to the consumer pulling back on autos and other durable goods that go with housing,'' said economist <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Aubrey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> G. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lanston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` It was that high interest rate environment that was really the major source of the weakness.'' Until recently, the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> has been pushing up interest rates in an attempt to cool inflationary pressures without slowing economic growth so much that the economy slides into a recession. <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Jasinowski </PERSON>, chief economist for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturers </ORGANIZATION>, said Friday's reports `` are not indications of an emerging slide into recession.'' `` Rather, they should be viewed as the temporary softenss that is likely to be associated with a soft-landing scenario for the economy,'' he said. Analysts also saw the decline in the factory operating rate as further lessening of inflationary pressures. The closer that industry gets to full operating capacity, the greater difficulty it has producing enough to meet demand, leading to shortages and price increases. `` The decline in capacity utilization _ which reflects increased capital investment as well as slower output growth _ provides additional confirmation that contrary to previous fears, the economy is not in danger of capacity shortages,'' <PERSON> Jasinowski </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dederick </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Northern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> said operating rates for iron, steel, paper and industrial chemicals are down. `` These are the industries that were so strong earlier and where a lot of the inflation was occurring,'' he said. The manufacturing plant operating rate fell 0.3 percentage point to 83.8 percent, down from May's 84.1 percent. Prior to April, the rate had declined since it peaked at 84.7 percent in January. The rate at factories producing durable goods, big-ticket items expected to last more than three years, fell 0.3 percentage point from 82.7 percent in May. This reflected in large part a reduction in the production of cars. The rate at factories producing non-durable goods dropped to 85.8 percent, compared with May's 86.0 percent. Production remained flat at manufacturing plants making both durable and non-durable goods. Output at mines and oil wells fell 1.1 percent after a revised 0.3 percent decline in May. Production at utilities dropped 1.3 percent in June after a 0.2 percent drop in May. <PERSON> Jasinowski </PERSON> said output of energy materials should increase when coal strikes are settled. More than 30,000 coal miners have been on strike for over a month in <LOCATION> Appalachia </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Jasinowski </PERSON> also said warmer weather demands for electric power would result in increased utility production this summer. Last month's factory operating rate was up from 83 percent a year earlier. The industrial production index was 3.4 percent higher than a year ago.
