<HEAD>KGB Chief Confirmed, But Told to Stop Spying on Soviets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soviet lawmakers voted overwhelmingly Friday to let the <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> chief keep his job, but they told him to stop spying on ordinary citizens and laughed in disbelief when he insisted the agency does n't tap telephones. It was the first time a <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> chief had stood up in public to justify the actions of the secretive intelligence agency, which is blamed for killing millions during <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>'s rule. Political reforms gave the Supreme Soviet the power to reject Cabinet-level appointees, and the official <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> news agency quoted <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> chief <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> Kryuchkov </PERSON> as saying Thursday's questioning was the most difficult examination of his life. But in the end, only six of the 542 deputies in the Supreme Soviet voted against his confirmation. Twenty-six deputies abstained. <PERSON> Kryuchkov </PERSON> has been <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> chairman since last year and was deputy chairman for 10 years before that. Deputies submitted written questions, and <PERSON> Kryuchkov </PERSON> read them himself, reducing the stinging tone. `` By what right do you tap people's telephones?'' asked one legislator. Derisive snorts of laughter greeted <PERSON> Kryuchkov </PERSON>'s answer that the <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> does not bug telephones of Soviet citizens. Maverick Communist <PERSON> Boris </PERSON> <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> told Western reporters during a break he did not believe it. <PERSON> Kryuchkov </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION>, which performs both domestic and foreign security functions, `` strictly follows Soviet laws'' and has only a few `` helpers'' who inform on neighbors and colleagues. He said 30 Western spies have been captured in the last three years. <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> said in a speech later that there were agents in every Soviet institution, doing great moral damage with their snooping. But he said that during the 10 years he was <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> chief in the city of <LOCATION> Sverdlovsk </LOCATION>, the agents `` never caught a single spy.'' <PERSON> Marju </PERSON> <PERSON> Lauristin </PERSON>, a professor and reform leader from <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION>, told deputies that many students have told her they were offered money within the past year to inform on other students and teachers. The balding, spectacled <PERSON> Kryuchkov </PERSON> responded to questions at rapid-fire speed but provided few real answers. He refused to reveal the <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION>'s budget despite repeated inquiries but said it would be published soon. He also refused to say how many employees the <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> has, but he said its border guard contingent alone numbers 200,000. <PERSON> Kryuchkov </PERSON> also said the <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> does not maintain dossiers on any dissidents except those who present a threat to the state. He did disclose that he was personally involved in starting the controversial investigation of a pair of popular prosecutors, who claim they ran into trouble when their investigation of corruption reached into the ruling Politburo. <PERSON> Kryuchkov </PERSON> said he thought of the prosecutors _ <LOCATION> Telman </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gdlyan </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Nikolai </PERSON> <PERSON> Ivanov </PERSON> _ as `` legends'' when he became <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> chairman but that within a week, his staff suggested they were guilty of coercing confessions. <PERSON> Kryuchkov </PERSON> said he alerted the chief prosecutor and they found substance to the allegations. <PERSON> Kryuchkov </PERSON> also admitted the <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> should have done a better job dealing with recent ethnic rioting in the republic of <LOCATION> Uzbekistan </LOCATION