<HEAD>Hungarians Pay Final Tribute to Former Communist Leader</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Janos </PERSON> <PERSON> Kadar </PERSON>, who led the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> for 32 years until losing power to a new generation of reformers, was buried Friday and praised as an early advocate of change. Thousands of people attended the somber state ceremony, which culminated two days of emotional tribute to the 77-year-old leader who died July 6, 14 months after his ouster. `` His great merit was to become a reformer in an age of rigidity,'' said President <PERSON> Bruno </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Straub </PERSON>, referring to <PERSON> Kadar </PERSON>'s cautious support of economic reforms in the late 1960s and early 1970s Party chairman <PERSON> Rezsoe </PERSON> <PERSON> Nyers </PERSON>, the architect of pioneering economic reforms in the late 1960s, said <PERSON> Kadar </PERSON>'s name `` has become inseparable from the Hungarian cause and international progress.'' Neither speaker alluded to the criticism of <PERSON> Kadar </PERSON> that followed his ouster as party leader in May 1988. Thousands of Hungarians lined the streets as the black Mercedes hearst carrying <PERSON> Kadar </PERSON>'s body slowly made its way from the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> building in downtown <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Kerepesi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cemetery </LOCATION>, where top-level communist officials are traditionally interred. <PERSON> Kadar </PERSON>'s rule began amid the bloodshed of the 1956 anti-Stalinist revolt as Soviet troops and tanks entered <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION> to quell the uprising. It ended 32 years later, when party leaders increasingly viewed him as an obstacle to change. <PERSON> Kadar </PERSON>'s body lay in state for two days in the gallery of the party's <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> building, and officials said more than 60,000 people had come to p