so was stripped of his membership in the policy-setting <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, which criticized him for mistakes during his rule. It was under <PERSON> Kadar </PERSON>'s rule that the 1956 uprising was officially dubbed a counterrevolution and its leader, <PERSON> Imre </PERSON> <PERSON> Nagy </PERSON>, was executed. The Communist Party recently re-evaluated the uprising as a popular revolt, and <PERSON> Nagy </PERSON> was rehabilitated. His remains were reburied in an elaborate ceremony June 16 that was attended by hundreds of thousands of Hungarians. Only hours after <PERSON> Kadar </PERSON>'s death, the <ORGANIZATION> Hungarian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> declared <PERSON> Nagy </PERSON> innocent of all charges.
