<BYLINE>By JULIETTE SAINTON</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 POINTE-A-PITRE, <LOCATION> Guadeloupe </LOCATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- _ <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Indians </LOCATION> celebrated Bastille Day with parades and a cultural festival featuring hundreds of artists, dancers and singers from 15 Caribbean nations. Guadeloupean independence activist <PERSON> Luc </PERSON> <PERSON> Reinette </PERSON> was greeted by a crowd of about 500 cheering supporters late Thursday night as he stepped off a plane from <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>. Reinette and seven other Guadeloupean nationalists jailed since the early 1980s on charges of terrorism were granted amnesty Wednesday by the French government, a gesture aimed at coinciding with the bicentennial of the French Revolution. Local television and radio broadcast the Bastille Day celebrations in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> Thursday and Friday. Bicentennial revelers in Pointe-a-Pitre watched <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> air force Mirage jets that flew from <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> this week perform low-level acrobatics, leaving trails of blue, white and red smoke, the colors of the French flag. Thousands of army conscripts marched in parades in Pointe-a-Pitre and <LOCATION> Basse-Terre </LOCATION>, the two largest cities of <LOCATION> Guadeloupe </LOCATION>, and in <LOCATION> Fort-de-France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Martinique </LOCATION>. As overseas departments, the eastern <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> islands of <LOCATION> Martinique </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Guadeloupe </LOCATION>, each with a population of 340,000, are integral parts of <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>. The theme of the Guadeloupean Arts Festival was the bicentennial of the French Revolution, symbolized by the July 14, 1789, storming of the Bastille prison by a Parisian mob. Several policemen accompanied Reinette on the flight, and more than a hundred were at the airport to prevent disorder when the independence leader arrived. <PERSON> Reinette </PERSON> was also greeted by his parents, wife, and two children. `` <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> should not think it is off the hook by freeing us,'' <PERSON> Reinette </PERSON> told the crowd at Le Raizet International Airport. `` <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> must initiate a veritable dialogue.'' The independence movement is virtually non-existent in <LOCATION> Martinique </LOCATION> and has never garnered more than 5 percent in elections in <LOCATION> Guadeloupe </LOCATION>. After a wave of terrorist bombings here in the early 1980s left eight people dead, <PERSON> Reinette </PERSON> was arrested in 1984, escaped shortly afterwards and was arrested again in 1987 and jailed in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>. The bombings ended with his arrest. <PERSON> Reinette </PERSON> was the leader of the outlawed <ORGANIZATION> Caribbean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION>. Nations and territories represented at the festival included <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virgin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Dominican </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kitts </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Dominica </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Martinique </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lucia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Barbados </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vincent </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Trinidad </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Anguilla </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Antigua </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Guiana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>.
