<HEAD>Negotiators Reach Tentative Agreement on S&amp;L Rules</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Congressional negotiators, breaking a procedural deadlock, tentatively agreed Friday to toughen proposed regulations on savings and loans as part of a $ 157 billion taxpayer bailout of the industry. Although nothing was adopted, <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> conferees moved toward embracing a combination of the toughest specific capital requirements in separate <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> bills to make S & amp; Ls back up loans with more of their own money. The conferees are trying to meld some of the most stringent features of both bills aimed at reforming S & amp; L abuses into one legislative package acceptable to both houses. Lax laws and accounting practices that let some thrifts lend federally insured deposits for risky and often fraudulent ventures while risking no money of their own is widely blamed as the chief factor behind the <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; L crisis, the largest financial debacle since the Depression. Covering the estimated $ 100 billion in losses is expected to cost each of the nation's taxpayers between $ 500 and $ 1,500 over the next 30 years. Differences in the way the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> have approached the <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; L legislation flared Thursday when the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> offered a comprehensive package and asked the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> to counter with an all-encompassing proposal of its own. `` Except for financing, we're not very far apart,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Jake </PERSON> <PERSON> Garn </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>, the ranking Republican senator in the conference. `` To go through them one-by-one, we might be here past Labor Day.'' The chief <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> conferee, Rep. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, balked, calling the move a `` horrendous injustice'' to an earlier agreement to tackle one-by-one each of the hundreds of differences between the two bills. But after examining a rough outline of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s proposal overnight, <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON> said Friday that the two sides were `` so close on an overwhelming majority'' that the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> would try to put together a counteroffer Monday. `` ` My intention is to provide a starting point for an overall settlement,'' he told the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> negotiators. `` I believe this provides the basis for us to resolve the impasse.'' Later Friday, however, <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> conferees balked at <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON>'s suggestion to accept a Senate-proposed timetable that would make S & amp; Ls meet the toughest of the new capital requirements immediately upon the bill's enactment rather than in June 1990, as in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> bill `` We have to have some minimal amount of time before the regulations are issued,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Schumer </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, one of the most vehement supporters of making S & amp; L owners put more of their own money at risk. As passed in its original form, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> bill would not have imposed the new requirements until June 1991. That issue, like dozens of others, remained unresolved. Nonetheless, <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON> said he was optimistic that the two sides can iron out their major differences by Wednesday, with the possible exception for how to raise the immediate $ 50 billion cost of the bailout. To prevent the bailout from swelling the federal deficit, President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZ