<PERSON> Smith </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lady </PERSON> <PERSON> Richardson </PERSON>, widow of Sir <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Richardson </PERSON>. <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Hopkins </PERSON>, who recently played King <PERSON> Lear </PERSON> at the <LOCATION> Olivier </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Theater </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, paid the final tribute by reading the closing six lines from the <PERSON> Shakespeare </PERSON> play, one of <PERSON> Olivier </PERSON>'s most famous roles: `` I have a journey, sir, shortly to go; `` My master calls me, I must not say no. `` The weight of this sad time we must obey; `` Speak what we feel, not what we ought to say. `` The oldest hath borne most: we that are young `` Shall never see so much, nor live so long.'' The service began with one of <PERSON> Olivier </PERSON>'s favorite hymns, `` The King of Love My Shepherd Is.'' It was sung last year at the christening of his grandson, Troilus. <PERSON> Tarquin </PERSON>, <PERSON> Olivier </PERSON>'s son from his first marriage, to <PERSON> Jill </PERSON> <PERSON> Esmond </PERSON>, read the first lesson from the Book of <LOCATION> Ecclesiastes </LOCATION>: `` Let us now praise famous men.'' His 27-year-old son <PERSON> Richard </PERSON>, from his marriage to Miss <PERSON> Plowright </PERSON>, gave the second reading from the First Book of <LOCATION> Corinthians </LOCATION>: `` Death, where is thy sting?'' Prayers were led by the Rev. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Burch </PERSON> and the mourners joined in singing the final hymn, `` God Be In My Head.'' After the service, Miss <PERSON> Plowright </PERSON> got into a limousine with her two daughters, <PERSON> Tamsin </PERSON>, 23, and Julie-Kate, 21, and the mourners drove across the <LOCATION> Sussex </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Downs </LOCATION> for a private cremation service at <LOCATION> Findon </LOCATION>, near <LOCATION> Worthing </LOCATION>. The family asked that anyone wishing to honor Lord <PERSON>