<HEAD>U.S. Willing to Arrange Loan to Aid Mexico in Debt Talks</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Summit Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, trying to knock down the last hurdles to its new Third World debt strategy, has promised to arrange as much as $ 2 billion in loans for financially strapped <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, officials said Friday. French President <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, burdened by a whopping $ 100 billion in foreign debt, urgently needs help. `` Mexico,'' he told French television, `` is on the edge of an explosion because of the weight of its debt and the impossibility of carrying the burden.'' `` No one,'' he said, `` has an interest in this explosion taking place, which would mean more misery for a suffering people.'' <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> is the test case of the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration's approach for easing the $ 1.3 trillion debt of poor nations. The strategy, representing a marked shift in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> policy, emphasizes debt reduction or forgiveness. <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> has been holding intense negotiations with private banks to reach an accord to show off at the annual economic summit of the world's seven big democracies, which got under way Friday. But Treasury Secretary <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> said it was unclear when <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and private bankers would wind up their bargaining, which began in mid-April. `` Whether or not the negotiations will proceed far enough to have closure by this weekend, we do n't know. We did n't set any deadlines,'' he told a news conference. `` But they're in good shape.'' The summit, he said, `` would be a suitable event to have that arrangement announced while we were here.'' White House Chief of Staff <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON> emphasized earlier, however, that `` the quality of the solution is more important that the timetable.'' The unrelieved debt problem was high on the summit agenda of President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and the leaders of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. They were expected to discuss it in detail Saturday. The summit began at the same time that <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> was marking the 200th anniversary of its revolution, a celebration that has attracted some three-dozen leaders of the world's richest and poorest nations. The poor have taken the opportunity to lobby their wealthier counterparts for help. But it was highly unlikely the rich democracies would respond with any dramatic proposal. <PERSON> Nigel </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s chancellor of the exchequer, said, `` What is important is we have agreed -LRB- on -RRB- this extension of the debt strategy,'' referring to the <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> plan. `` And the commerical banks need to be absolutely clear there is no new initiative coming forward,'' he said. `` That is the position, and it is up to them to negotiate a debt-reduction agreement with the debtor countries, starting with <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> held a hastily arranged meeting Friday morning with Mexican President <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gortari </PERSON> to discuss the debt issues. <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gortari </PERSON> met earlier in the week with German Chancellor <PERSON> Helmut </PERSON> <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> and Japanese Prime Minister <PERSON> Sousuke </PERSON> <PERSON> Uno </PERSON> to press his case. White House officials confirmed reports that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was willing to arrange a $ 1 billion to $ 2 billion bridge loan to help <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> meet its financial obligations until a final debt deal is in place. `` We would be willing to do this with other countries if <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and the their banks can get together,'' <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> said. `` We have indications that other -LRB- industrialized nations -RRB- would be willing to join as well.'' <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> has received similar loans from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in the past to help it close the gap between its financial obligations and the amount of money left in its coffers. A bridge loan helps sweeten a deal because it ensures bankers the debtor nation will continue making interest payments. <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, which is believed to be running low on foreign reserves, is the developing world's second largest debtor after <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> owes private lenders $ 54 billion, with about $ 15 billion due American banks. In its negotiations with a 15-member bank panel, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> has pressed for sharp cuts in both its overall debt and its annual interest fees, which run about $ 10 billion a year. By reducing those charges, the <LOCATION> Mexican </LOCATION> government would have more money left from foreign earnings to pump into its flat economy. <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> wants to cut its annual interest fees from 6 percent of its gross domestic product, the total value of a nation's economic output, to 2 percent. It went into the talks demanding a 55 percent discount on a portion of its $ 54 billion private debt. Bankers countered with a 22 percent discount. The two sides, sources said, have tentatively centered on a 35 percent cut. To do that, negotiators are discussing a variety of options, including swapping old debt for new, guaranteed bonds, and putting up new loans to dilute the debt concentration.
