<BYLINE>By DOUG FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The captain of a Greek tanker who already faced federal pollution charges after the ship ran aground off <LOCATION> Newport </LOCATION>, spilling thousands of gallons of oil, on Friday was indicted on two state felony counts. <PERSON> Iakovos </PERSON> <PERSON> Georgudis </PERSON>, 43, of <LOCATION> Athens </LOCATION> was charged with failure to have a harbor pilot on board the World Prodigy at the time of the June 23 spill and with polluting the coastal waters, Attorney General <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Neil </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> says about 300,000 gallons of toxic No. 2 heating oil spilled into <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sound </LOCATION> at the entrance to <LOCATION> Narragansett </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION>. Most of the oil, which was lighter than the crude oil that has fouled <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> waters since March, has now been cleaned up or dissipated. The failure to have a pilot on board carries a potential penalty of $ 10,000 and one year in jail, <PERSON> O'Neil </PERSON> said. The pollution count carries up to 30 days in jail and a $ 10,000 fine. <PERSON> O'Neil </PERSON>, however, indicated that <PERSON> Georgudis </PERSON>, 43, was unlikely to spend time in jail, even if convicted. `` What we're looking at here are fines right now,'' <PERSON> O'Neil </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Georgudis </PERSON>, who is in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, where the ship is being repaired, likely will surrender to <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> authorities within the next week to 10 days for arraignment, <PERSON> O'Neil </PERSON> said. The attorney general said <PERSON> Georgudis </PERSON>' attorney, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> DiBiase </PERSON>, had indicated the captain would cooperate. <PERSON> Georgudis </PERSON> also faces federal counts of violating the Clean Water Act and the Refuse Act, which prohibit dumping of pollutants. He has admitted making a mistake and steering the ship in the wrong direction onto the reef, according to Gov. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> DiPrete </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> officials who have interviewed him. A statewide grand jury began meeting in the week after the accident and the indictments were expected. <PERSON> Georgudis </PERSON> refused to testify in front of the grand jury or a <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> inquiry into the grounding, citing his right not to be forced to incriminate himself. The indictment charges that <PERSON> Georgudis </PERSON> ran the World Prodigy onto the rocks through `` gross negligence.'' The ship's helmsman testified during the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> inquiry that he spotted a red buoy warning of the reef on the left side of the ship, when it should have been on the right, as the World Prodigy approached the harbor but he did not tell the captain. The harbor pilot who was supposed to meet the tanker said he tried to warn it away from the rocks three times but saw no response. <PERSON> O'Neil </PERSON> said most of his office's efforts were going to recovering the costs of the spill from the ship's owner, <ORGANIZATION> Ballard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shiopping </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> has estimated the costs at almost $ 2 million, but <PERSON> O'Neil </PERSON> said the state costs were not fully tallied. The attorney general said <PERSON> Ballard </PERSON> and its insurance company so far had cooperated in the assessment of damages. `` We're fortunate they're insured. We're fortunate they have an owner who seems to have some social conscience,'' <PERSON> O'Neil </PERSON> said.
