<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KFAR AKUB, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Ola </PERSON> <PERSON> Fareh </PERSON> <PERSON> Awad </PERSON> is among thousands of <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> teen-agers enmeshed in the Israeli judicial system because of stone-throwing, and could be sent to prison for 20 years. Miss <PERSON> Awad </PERSON>, a 14-year-old American citizen who lives in this Palestinian village north of <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>, is accused along with three friends of `` acting with intention to endanger public life'' by throwing rocks at an intercity bus in December. She was 13 at the time, and says they were innocent bystanders. `` We were walking home from school and saw the bus stop,'' she said in an interview. `` Jewish people got out and started shooting in the air. We were scared and ran away, but they caught us and hit us and said we threw the stones.'' <PERSON> Uzi </PERSON> <PERSON> Hasson </PERSON>, the Israeli chief prosecutor, said no one was hurt but the glass in the rear door of the bus was broken and the passengers were endangered. `` We are pursuing the case because we take stone-throwing very seriously,'' he said. `` I do n't wish anybody to be in such an attack. You are helpless. If you're driving, it can be very dangerous.'' More than 1,500 Israeli soldiers and civilians have been injured, nearly all by stones, since the Palestinian uprising in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> began more than 19 months ago. At least 560 Palestinians and 35 Israelis have been killed, mainly by gunfire or means other than stones, and more than 8,000 Palestinians have been wounded. <PERSON> Hasson </PERSON> said conviction on the charge against the girls carries a maximum of 20 years, but the average jail sentence has been about 15 months. <PERSON> Jawad </PERSON> <PERSON> Boulos </PERSON>, Miss <PERSON> Awad </PERSON>'s lawyer, said the case could drag on for months because of overloaded court calendars. `` I think this is symptomatic of the insanity of the Israeli judicial system,'' he said. `` They are trying to teach the girls a lesson and deter them and others from having a part in the uprising. This is n't the way to influence people.'' Miss <PERSON> Awad </PERSON> said interrogators slapped her and threatened to put her in jail if she refused to confess. Before being sent home, she and her mother, <PERSON> Jamileh </PERSON>, had to sign a statement agreeing to an automatic three-month prison sentence if <PERSON> Ola </PERSON> was detained for another alleged offense. Apparently because she was only 13 at the time her arrest, authorities allowed Miss Awad to return to her ninth grade class at the Holy Rosary School. Her Palestinian companions, aged 15 and 16, were held for several months in a makeshift detention center in a convent, then put under house arrest. <PERSON> Ola </PERSON> <PERSON> Awad </PERSON> never lived in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, but her father worked in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> until his death in 1983. She is among 16 holders of American passports who have been caught up in the judicial system since the uprising began. According to the army, nearly 8,600 Palestinians from the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> are in detention in cases related to the uprising, most of them involving stone-throwing. About 7,000 Palestinian-Americans are among the 1 million Arabs in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials estimate. About 100 holders of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> passports are among the <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>'s 700,000 residents. The Americans in detention include <PERSON> Mansour </PERSON> <PERSON> Abed </PERSON> <PERSON> al </PERSON> <PERSON> Samad </PERSON>, 16, born in <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ric