<HEAD>Principal Sacrifices Job For Students</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A principal who told officials that students needed teachers more than they needed him at his financially pressed elementary school of 200 was out of a job Friday. Some board members had tears in their eyes Thursday night when they voted unanimously to lay off <PERSON> Principal </PERSON> <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> <PERSON> Najimy </PERSON>. His teachers wept openly. `` This was the shortest and saddest meeting in our history,'' said board member <PERSON> Donna </PERSON> <PERSON> Slowick </PERSON>. `` No one seemed to believe it would really happen, but me, `` <PERSON> Najimy </PERSON>, a teacher for 37 years, said by telephone Friday. `` But with the governor's announcement of further state aid cuts, there was no way.'' Hours before the school committee met, Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> announced he was vetoing $ 491 million in state spending, including cuts in community and education aid, because of the state's own fiscal problems. `` He is a public servant, a teacher, who stood up to be counted and put his own personal welfare behind what is best for the kids,'' said <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, deputy state education commissioner. `` Our hearts go out to the parents, kids, teachers and the school committee, who had to make a very difficult decision.'' `` I did n't want to go. I still have one child in college,'' said <PERSON> Najimy </PERSON>, as friends and distraught parents rallied around him and several school superintendents called with job offers. `` But what would you do with the children without teachers?'' Maintaining the children needed the teachers more, <PERSON> Najimy </PERSON> suggested last month that <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION> could save about $ 40,000 by firing him and paying a teacher an extra $ 3,000 to run the school. `` Building faculty is the hardest thing to do,'' he said at the time. `` If we lose our teachers, we will never get them back.'' `` The irony is we had built an award-winning school,'' <PERSON> Najimy </PERSON> said. Last year, the school was cited by the <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Improvement </ORGANIZATION> and the state <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Najimy </PERSON> was named a fellow of the <ORGANIZATION> Commonwealth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Leadership </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> and commissioned by the education department to conduct a study of the future of education. `` Educators in several states are using my monograph to plan their programs for the 1990s,'' <PERSON> Najimy </PERSON> said. `` And here I am looking for a job.'' A professional Shakespearian company also spent 12 weeks in residence at the school under a state Arts Council grant. A student-built nature trail, illustrated with the children's own poetry, was created with the help of a poet and a master calligrapher, who brought their art into the classrooms. `` I think the thing that makes me the angriest is the hypocrisy of saying that education is the key to our future at the same time we are unwilling to give the children the resources to cope with a legacy of $ 2 trillion in debt, a polluted environment and other social problems,'' <PERSON> Najimy </PERSON> said.
