<HEAD>Senate Urges Economic Sanctions Against China</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 EDs: INSERTS new 5th-7th grafs, bgng, Reacting to, etc., to insert with White House reaction from <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> voted 81-10 on Friday to impose economic sanctions against <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and to urge President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to take even harshar measures. The legislation was offered by <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Majority Leader <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> `` to express to the government of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> the concern which the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people feel about the continuing prosecution of <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> students and workers who support the pro-democracy movement,'' <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> said. It calls on <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to make sure the leaders of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> understand `` that until they recognize the <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> people's legitimate desire for democracy, human rights and justice, that relations between our two countries will remain strained.'' The sanctions amendment was attached to pending legislation authorizing $ 4.66 billion for the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and allied agencies during the fiscal year beginning next Oct. 1. Reacting to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> action, <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> told reporters in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, `` We feel that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has imposed sanctions that are meaningful and that adequately convey our sense of condemnation of the events that occurred in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. We also believe that we need to be mindful of long-term relationships with that country as we move forward.'' He said there is a `` fair degree of unanimity'' among the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>' summit partners on the issue. He said the administration would consider the legislation `` but generally speaking, we think we have taken the right course, that that has been recognized by other nations of the world. We feel it's also supported and recognized by the American public. <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> noted that while the amendment requires the president to suspend certain trade programs, it also has a provision which `` gives him the flexibility to cease any suspension or termination ... if he finds it in the security interest of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to do so.'' The measure adopts several sanctions adopted earlier by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>. These include six-month suspensions of trade insurance by the <ORGANIZATION> Overseas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Private </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and the use of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> funds to support trade with <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. Other sanctions include the suspension of export of satellites intended to be launched by <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and the suspension of nuclear cooperation until the president can certify <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> is not involved in nuclear proliferation. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> also adopted a series of non-binding suggestions in which they urged <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to take stiffer steps. He should, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> said: _ Direct the <LOCATION> Export-Import </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> to immediately postpone approval of applications for financing American exports to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> _ Instruct <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> representatives at international financial institutions to oppose all loans to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> _ Review the advisability of continuing to extend to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> most-favored-nation trade treatment _ Review all trade agreements between the two countries _ Review commercial agreements governing Chinese-American cooperation on satellite launches _ Review the Chinese-American agreement on the peaceful uses of atomic energy _ Consult with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> allies at the upcoming economic summit in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> on adopting a collective economic response to repression in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> _ Review high technology exports to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> Senate Republican Leader <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> endorsed the amendment, saying the <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> government has `` shown no signs of relenting'' in its persecution of those who took part in or appeared to encourage the pro-democracy demonstrations. `` They are still sliding down a very slippery and dangerous slope,'' <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> said. Those voting against the sanctions amendment were Sens. Kit Bond, R-Mo.; <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Boren </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Okla </LOCATION>.; <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Chafee </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-R.I. </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Thad </PERSON> <PERSON> Cochran </PERSON>, R-Miss; <PERSON> Kent </PERSON> <PERSON> Conrad </PERSON>, D-N.D.; <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Durenberger </PERSON>, R-Minn.; <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Lugar </PERSON>, R-Ind; <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> <PERSON> Rudman </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.H. </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Arlen </PERSON> <PERSON> Specter </PERSON>, R-Pa.; and <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Alaska </LOCATION> Those not voting were Sens. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Armstrong </PERSON>, R-Colo.; <PERSON> Dale </PERSON> <PERSON> Bumpers </PERSON>, D-Ark; <PERSON> Quentin </PERSON> <PERSON> Burdick </PERSON>, D-N.D.: <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Danforth </PERSON>, R-Mo.; <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jeffords </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Vt </LOCATION>.; <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, D-Mass; <PERSON> Spark </PERSON> <PERSON> Matsunaga </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Hawaii </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Mikulski </PERSON>, D-Md.; and <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Simpson </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Wyo </LOCATION>.
