<HEAD>Syrian-Christian Artillery Battle over Tanker</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE number of dead and wounded and
with fighting continuing into the night; pickup 6th graf pvs, `A spokesman...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An oil tanker sailed past a <LOCATION> Syrian </LOCATION> naval blockade Friday and docked at a Christian port, triggering an artillery duel between <LOCATION> Syrian </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> gunners that killed seven people and wounded 12. The thud of exploding shells and whooshing sound of rockets echoed across <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> as Syrian gunners opened up on the Christian-controlled coast north of the capital. The fighting continued late into the night. A police spokesman said the unidentified tanker, which arrived at an undisclosed harbor north of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, was the second to reach the Christian enclave in the past two days with a cargo of badly needed fuel. On Wednesday, another tanker unloaded gasoline at <LOCATION> Byblos </LOCATION> port, 18 miles north of the capital. The deaths from the artillery duel raised the overall toll to 416 killed and 1,627 wounded since the current confrontation erupted March 8 between Christian army commander Gen. <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>'s 20,000 troops and <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>'s 40,000-member force in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. A spokesman for <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>'s command, speaking on condition of anonymity, said a Syrian gunboat intercepted the latest tanker in Lebanese territorial waters early in the day, searched it for weapons and ammunition and `` allowed the captain to resume his voyage. `` I do n't understand why Syrian gunners shelled the ship after the <LOCATION> Syrian </LOCATION> gunboat permitted it to continue,'' said the spokesman, who refused to give any details about the tanker and its cargo, citing `` security considerations.'' He said the Syrians shelled the Christian coast from positions in Moslem west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> and the northern town of <LOCATION> Salaata </LOCATION>, on the edge of the 310-square-mile enclave. He said <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>'s gunners scored `` several direct hits on Syrian artillery emplacements in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> and the north.'' However, the claim could not be independently verified. Shells exploded near the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Beirut </ORGANIZATION> in the city's Moslem sector, witnesses said. The Syrian military headquarters in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> refused to comment. A police spokesman, who can not be named in line with standing rules, said Syrian barrage concentrated on the 28-mile Christian stretch of <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s 130-mile Mediterranean coast. The Syrians have besieged the Christian enclave since March 12 in retaliation for a blockade <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> ordered of illegal ports run by Syrian-backed militias south of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> that he said were depriving his government of $ 100 million a year in tax revenue. The Syrian navy joined the blockade earlier this month after <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> claimed <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> obtained Soviet-designed Frog-7 missiles from its traditional Arab rival, <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. The missiles are capable of hitting <LOCATION> Damascus </LOCATION>, the Syrian capital. <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> and his aides have refused to confirm or deny that they have Frog-7 missiles, but <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> said Thursday that <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> has the missiles, which have a range of more than 40 miles. An editorial in the official daily newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Al-Thawra </ORGANIZATION>, controlled by President <PERSON> Saddam </PERSON> <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON>'s ruling <ORGANIZATION> Arab </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Baath </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> party </ORGANIZATION>, said <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> was `` expressing fear of missiles received by the regular Lebanese army.'' It did not elaborate. <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> are ruled by rival wings of the Baath party. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> has declared support for <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>'s `` war of liberation'' against Syrian forces which entered <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> in 1976 under an Arab League peacekeeping mandate. <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> and other Christian leaders accuse the Syrians of betraying their mandate by siding with the Moslems in the 14-year-old civil war which has killed more than 150,000 people.
