<HEAD>Walesa Will Support Any Communist Presidential Candidate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Solidarity leader <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> said Friday that <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> needs a president immediately to resolve a constitutional crisis, and he will support anyone the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> puts up. The president is to be elected by a joint vote of the both houses of the new parliament, in which Solidarity is strongly represented. Gen. <PERSON> Wojciech </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> chief, said June 30 he would not run for the new, more powerful presidency because he was too closely linked with the martial law he imposed in December 1981 to crush Solidarity. Under agreements signed in April, the independent labor union was made legal again and <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> held its freest postwar elections, in which Solidarity trounced the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. In a statement released by an aide, <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> said Friday: `` I will cooperate with any president elected ... no matter if it is Gen. <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON>, Gen. <PERSON> Czeslaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Kiszczak </PERSON> or some other representative'' of the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> `` in order to solve Polish problems.'' When <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON> said he would not seek the presidency he recommended <PERSON> Kiszczak </PERSON>, who is interior minister and negotiated the April accords with Solidarity, but the party leadership asked him to reconsider his own candidacy. <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON> has re-emerged as a likely candidate, especially after appearing frequently with <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> during the American president's three-day visit. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s domestic and international situation requires a president, and `` the election ... should be held immediately.'' `` Our country faces a great chance, but at the same time we have a constitutional crisis connected with a delay in filling the president's office,'' he said. `` Extension of this situation causes additional dangers.'' <PERSON> Mikolaj </PERSON> <PERSON> Kozakiewicz </PERSON>, speaker of the <ORGANIZATION> Sejm </ORGANIZATION>, the former unicameral parliament and now the lower house, said Thursday the election might take place by July 22, <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s national day. <PERSON> Kozakiewicz </PERSON> said the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> visit had eased controversy about <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON>'s candidacy, but many Solidarity legislators were jailed during martial law and have said they will not vote for <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON>. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> is not a member of the parliament and, in his statement, did not instruct Solidarity representatives how to vote.
