<HEAD>Policy Liberalization Will Help Align Beef Industries</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Recent liberalization of policies will help align the beef industries in a number of <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rim </LOCATION> countries that share trading interests with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, an <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> report said Friday. Other affected countries include <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>, according to a report by the department's <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> `` The trade flows resulting from liberalization will be directly influenced by underlying patterns in beef production and consumption in these countries,'' the report said. A decline in cattle inventories during the decade 1976-86 in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Oceania </LOCATION> appears to be ending, although per capita beef consumption `` may not rebound to earlier levels,'' the report said. `` Continued growth in beef consumption and market access in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> will become even more important to the beef-exporting countries.'' The report said diets of East Asians are shifting rapidly to more meats, dairy products, caloric sweeteners, and fats and oils, but less grain. `` In contrast, diets in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Oceania </LOCATION> are shifting to more grains and less beef,'' the report said.
