<HEAD>Writer Vargas Llosa Returns to Run for President</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with further comment from Vargas
Llosa, details of Peru's economic, social problems; no pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Novelist <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Vargas </PERSON> <PERSON> Llosa </PERSON> returned Friday from <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> to resume his presidential candidacy, 23 days after quitting the race in a dispute with members of his coalition. Hundreds of supporters waving flags and handkerchiefs greeted him with shouts of `` President <PERSON> Mario </PERSON>'' as he stepped off the plane. <PERSON> Vargas </PERSON> <PERSON> Llosa </PERSON> criticized the `` outdated, irresponsible and demagogic politics that have characterized <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> in recent years'' and that have been rejected by the `` vast majority'' of Peruvians, who are to vote for president next spring. He rode in a motorcade to his seaside home in a <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION> suburb, where he spoke to supporters from his balcony. `` In this moment, the only priority is the salvation of our fatherland, stopping its fall into impoverishment, incompetence and self-destruction,'' <PERSON> Vargas </PERSON> <PERSON> Llosa </PERSON> told the crowd. <PERSON> Vargas </PERSON> <PERSON> Llosa </PERSON> had sent a letter to party leaders in the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> when he quit the race June 22, saying he was dropping out because of `` petty and mediocre'' motives of some in the party. The leaders in the center-right coalition had disagreed over whether each party should field its own candidates in November's municipal elections <PERSON> Vargas </PERSON> <PERSON> Llosa </PERSON> said he could not be a candidate for the coalition without the united support of the parties. He said that support would be impossible if the parties had to battle each other in the local elections. The writer resumed his candidacy July 2 after the parties agreed to nominate single candidates representing the front in the elections, which are expected to be a test run for the presidential election, tentatively scheduled for April 1990. The Democratic Front is dominated by <PERSON> Vargas </PERSON> <PERSON> Llosa </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Liberty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION>, former President <PERSON> Fernando </PERSON> <PERSON> Belaunde </PERSON> <PERSON> Terry </PERSON>'s centrist <ORGANIZATION> Popular </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Action </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and the conservative <ORGANIZATION> Popular </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. Recent polls show the novelist comfortably leading his closest rival, former socialist <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> Alfonso </PERSON> <PERSON> Barrantes </PERSON>, candidate of a leftist coalition. <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Alva </PERSON> <PERSON> Castro </PERSON>, the candidate of the governing center-left <ORGANIZATION> Aprista </ORGANIZATION> party, is given little chance of winning because of voter discontent with President <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON>'s administration. <PERSON> Vargas </PERSON> <PERSON> Llosa </PERSON> is basing his campaign on radical, neo-liberal policies to reduce government intervention in the economy and to reduce the bloated bureaucracy. The ideas are popular with business and the middle class, whose incomes are being ravaged by inflation that reached 1,722 percent last year and is expected to exceed 6,000 percent this year. <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> has stopped payments on its $ 16.5 billion foreign debt, and has been cut off by the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>. The country is also facing a leftist insurgency that has left 15,000 people dead and caused $ 10 billion in damages, according to government figures. <PERSON> Vargas </PERSON> <PERSON> Llosa </PERSON>, often mentioned as a candidate for the Nobel Prize in literature, had gone to <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> to receive a literary award. He then traveled to <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>, where he said his ideas for dealing with <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>'s problems were widely supported. But his on-again, off-again candidacy has caused some analysts to question whether he can take the strain of a long campaign. `` Quitting once is a tragedy,'' said a <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> official who spoke on condition of anonymity. `` But quitting twice would be a comedy.''
