<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration is prepared to announce a compensation offer early next week for families of the non-Iranian victims on the <ORGANIZATION> Iran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> flight shot down by a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> warship a year ago, officials said Friday. All but 40 of the 290 people who died were Iranian. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has said it would pay compensation to all families, but the Iranian government has refused to provide details about its citizens who died, such as their ages. The 40 non-Iranians were Indians, Pakistanis, Koreans, Japanese and citizens of several Arab countries. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government has said it will not pay the Iranian government directly, and <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> has called that position `` not acceptable.'' In civil lawsuits arising from crash deaths in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, courts generally award compensation based on the lost earnings of a family member. Thus families of people who die early in lucrative careers usually win larger awards than families of retired people. It is not known whether such an approach would be followed in the government's compensation offer. The officials, who asked not to be identified, were unable to provide figures on the compensation package they expect but said a formal announcement was expected early next week. The absence of diplomatic relations, broken nine years ago when hostages were seized in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Embassy in <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION>, has complicated efforts to arrange payments for the Iranian victims. Testifying on the issue earlier this week, Assistant Secretary of State <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON> said that the administration hopes to be able to resolve the problems concerning compensation for the families of Iranian victims by working through third countries and non-government