<HEAD>Vertigo-Afflicted Mulroney Passes On Riding Bubble Elevator</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: FIXES typo in 2nd graf; pickup 3rd graf, `The sessions...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Rocketing 300 feet skyward in a plastic bubble mounted on a flimsy tower of piping is not every world leader's idea of a good time. Canadian Prime Minister <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON>, reputed to suffer vertigo at considerable heights, is taking another route to the cloud-bound confines of the 15th World Economic Summit at <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Grande </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arche </ORGANIZATION>. The sessions on debt, development and <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc aid bring the world's most influential western statesmen to the upper slab of a controversial structure that looks much like a deep, glassless window frame. The rooftop summit site is a windowless, marble-encased concrete cocoon that spans two trapezoidal office towers at a height of more than 300 feet. Many have likened the Arche's exposed elevator shaft to scaffolding, and two stands of metal-pipe artworks flanking the structure's entrance also give the site a `` Men at Work'' motif. To picture the Arche, imagine a 35-story-high white cardboard box standing on its side, with the top and bottom flaps folded in to form a free-standing tunnel. The cavernous hollow below the summit site is large enough to hold the Notre Dame cathedral, including its spire. <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON>'s spokesman, <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Lavoie </PERSON>, declined comment on a <ORGANIZATION> Le </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monde </ORGANIZATION> newspaper report Friday that the <LOCATION> Canadian </LOCATION> prime minister would forego the elevators because of a fear of heights. <PERSON> Lavoie </PERSON> said it was his understanding that all seven leaders attending the summit would avoid the bubbles for security reasons, and that <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON>'s attitude toward heights `` is a matter of his private life.'' Journalists who have accompanied <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> on other trips abroad, however, report that the prime minister categorically rejects all venues with exposed heights and even draws the curtains over windows of his jet when flying. Contrary to the Canadian view, at least one of the leaders is taking the scenic route. `` I ca n't imagine <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> passing up anything adventurous,'' <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> commented.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
