<FIRST>a e AM-APArts:ChineseMovie Adv17   07-14 0735</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: Chinese Movie, Adv 17,0751</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 17</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday AMs, July 17 and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Political Upheaval Gives Chinese Movie a Quiet Start</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Upstaged by political turmoil, `` The First Emperor of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'' had a quiet start instead of a gala premiere for its filmed re-enactments of Chinese history and spectacular views of the Great Wall. However, the <ORGANIZATION> Canadian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civilization </ORGANIZATION> has been attracting a lot of attention since the 40-minute documentary opened there July 4. `` There's obviously a disappointment on both our side and on the Chinese studio side,'' <PERSON> Barrie </PERSON> <PERSON> Howells </PERSON>, the film's Canadian producer, said about downplaying the movie's promotion. The $ 5.8 million movie in the huge Imax format is the first major attraction at the Cineplus theater of the new Canadian <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civilization </ORGANIZATION>. But its part in the June opening celebration for the museum was delayed to avoid controversy. Regular screenings of the film in English and French, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>'s two official languages, began July 4 on the theater's 87 - by 62-foot screen In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, the American Museum of Natural History took the movie off its summer schedule because of the situation in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. `` Basically, I feel the film has to be shown,'' <PERSON> Howells </PERSON> said in an interview. `` I look at it as a joint venture between a lot of Chinese workers and artists and Canadian filmmakers.'' `` The First Emperor'' is the first Imax film made in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and the first to place the emphasis on dramatic scenes rather than the showy travelogs known to visitors to Imax theaters in museums and special exhibitions. It is a co-production between the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Film </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Canada </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s Xi'an Film Studio, which approved the script. The documentary tells of <PERSON> Qin </PERSON> <PERSON> Shihuang </PERSON>, who built the Great Wall of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> but whose dynasty lasted only three years after his death in 210 B.C. In its retelling of the emperor's career, the film notes that books promoting freedom of thought were burned. `` The burning of them enraged the intellectuals of the day. <PERSON> Qin </PERSON> also had a solution for them,'' the narration, written by Chinese screenwriter <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> <PERSON> Ji </PERSON> <PERSON> Cheng </PERSON>, says. `` He buried 460 of them alive. The criticism stopped.'' The film otherwise is mostly filled with scenery and pageantry, which works better in the large Imax format than the few intimate scenes that tend to be stilted on a screen geared to spectacle. In addition, to the Great Wall, the documentary also shows some of the terra cotta army of 7,000 life-size statues that <PERSON> Qin </PERSON> left in his tomb. The site was discovered in 1974 by some workers digging a well in <LOCATION> Shaanxi </LOCATION> province, and the Canadians making `` The First Emperor'' were the first foreign crew allowed to film there. <PERSON> Howells </PERSON> said the collaboration of the Canadian and Chinese crews, filming from Oct. 30 to Feb. 13, was a big project and not an easy task. He said, however, that in retrospect those involved `` will say we did n't have any real major problem.'' He attributed most of the difficulties to confusion arising from translating and interpreting mistakes, or simply cultural differences. `` We'd meet every day at the end of the shoot of that day and sort out the problems,'' he said. As for logistics, among the props were 3,200 weapons, 40 chariots and some artifacts from the Qin dynasty. There were 11 studio sets, including a seven-story royal palace, and 20 locations. Nine Canadians and 368 Chinese were working on `` The First Emperor'' at the height of production. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Film </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> produced the first Imax film for <LOCATION> Montreal </LOCATION>'s Expo'67. With Imax, there's a high focus and ultra-clear picture, and sound comes from many directions. Seats are in curved rows and at a steep incline, so viewers get a full perspective and are made to feel like they're actually in the motion picture. The system since has spread to other countries, and more than 60 theaters now exist to show the films made from outer space to the deep sea. Although the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Film </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> takes credit for the idea of doing a documentary on Qin, it says the Chinese decided that the pageantry and spectacle would be best suited to an Imax production even though the first theater had yet to be built there. The first Chinese Imax theater was planned for <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
