<FIRST>a a BC-TickerTalk Adv17   07-14 0624</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Ticker Talk, Adv 17,0639</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv17</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday July 17</HEAD>
<HEAD>Investing With a Plan</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also on financial wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Of all the strategic errors people make when they invest their money, financial advisers say, by far the most common is to have no strategy at all. For many individual investors, this problem arises not so much from ignorance, laziness or disorganization, but rather from the ordinary vagaries of day-to-day life. Investments in stocks, mutual funds and other securities tend to be made at unpredictable intervals _ say, when a lump-sum payment is received, when a bank time deposit matures, or when investors happen on some idea that strikes their fancy. In many cases that's only natural. The typical small investor's savings and investment holdings are put together one piece at a time Unless they come into some windfall such as an inheritance, few people are in a position to create a $ 50,000, $ 100,000 or $ 500,000 `` portfolio'' with the wave of a checkbook. Granted, the experts say, but even those investors who have accumulated substantial sums in their accounts often sit with a patchwork of holdings that fit no overall pattern. This can leave them in a poor position to pursue their financial goals, and vulnerable to risks they never intended to take. `` Most investors buy one stock or bond at a time, without considering how it will affect the structure of the overall portfolio,'' observes <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Slatter </PERSON>, an analyst at the Cleveland-based brokerage firm of <PERSON> Prescott </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Ball </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Turben </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` Nearly all investors understand diversification,'' he adds. `` Nearly all investors believe diversification is worthwhile. But almost no one does anything about it.'' In its weekly publication The Outlook, <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Poor </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> summarized the problem: `` The best way to build an investment portfolio is with a well-conceived plan. `` A portfolio that is a haphazard mixture of stocks, some of which have been bought on hunches or tips, is unlikely to produce satisfactory results over the long term.'' <PERSON> Slatter </PERSON>, who has long experience examining the holdings of customers who ask for advice, says he sees some common tendencies: `` In a typical portfolio, there are too many public utilities _ often 40 percent or more. In many instances, there are too many bank stocks and oil stocks. `` Those seem to be the industries that appeal to the vast majority of investors. Yet there are at least 75 industries to choose from, some of which have done far better than utilities, banks or oils.'' Utility and bank issues may attract _ or have attracted in the past _ people looking for conservative stocks with relatively high yields. However, as <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; P points out, in the world of the late 1980s, investors who have a large percentage of their money in such stocks may find themselves over-exposed to the risks that come with wide fluctuations in interest rates. In the same vein, <PERSON> Slatter </PERSON> says, many people with ties to a large company through their jobs, their family or their communities wind up with a great chunk of their savings in a single stock. `` In most cases those investors are unwilling to part with a single share, even when that one stock makes up 80 percent of the portfolio,'' he notes. `` They seem to ignore the fact that any stock can go down.'' Who qualifies as a `` beginner'' investor with a need for mapping out a diversified strategy? It could be someone who has just sold a house or business, received a bonus or hit the lottery. Or, says S & amp; P, `` he or she may equally be someone who wants to start a focused investment program after years of dabbling in the market.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon July 17</NOTE>
</DOC>
