<HEAD>$Adv16</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, July 16</HEAD>
<HEAD>In Aftermath of Supreme Court Ruling, Abortion Battle Beginning Anew</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MITCHELL LANDSBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Less than two weeks after the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> upheld <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION>'s restrictive abortion law, battles have erupted in at least a half-dozen states in a preview of the war to be waged next year in legislatures across the country Versions of the <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> law have been introduced in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> and are being drafted in <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling has revived a long-dormant court battle over a law banning abortion. Anti-abortion legislators in at least 25 other states have begun planning legislation based on <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION>'s law, and abortion has suddenly become a major issue in governor's races in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>. `` It is going to be the major issue of 1990,'' said <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> Comptroller <PERSON> Roland </PERSON> <PERSON> Burris </PERSON>, a pro-choice Democrat who is exploring a possible run for governor. `` There's no in-between on this.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling on July 3 upheld a <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> law that banned abortions in public hospitals and stopped public employees from counseling women about abortions. It also required doctors planning to perform abortions to first test any fetus over 20 weeks to determine if it could live outside the womb. Many observers expect the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> to take up other abortion issues in its fall term, and possibly to overturn <PERSON> Roe </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Wade </PERSON>, the case that legalized abortion nationwide in 1973. But even if the court goes no further than the <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> case _ <PERSON> Webster </PERSON> vs. <ORGANIZATION> Reproductive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> _ it will have dramatically altered the political landscape in almost every state in the country. `` We really have to recognize that what <PERSON> Webster </PERSON> has done is reopen the abortion battle,'' said <PERSON> Burke </PERSON> <PERSON> Balch </PERSON>, the state legislative coordinator for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Right </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> to </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Life </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. Of 13 legislatures that may hold further sessions this year, <PERSON> Balch </PERSON> says battles over abortion were likely in seven _ <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>. He declined to characterize the prospects for change in those states or in most of the other states that likely will reconsider abortion laws next year. However, he did say Right to Life expects its most difficult battles in the 13 states that provide financing for abortions for poor women _ especially <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>. The states most likely to enact further abortion restrictions are <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION>, he said. <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> already has the most restrictive abortion law on the books, a statute making it a crime to perform an abortion. However, the law has lain dormant since 1976, when a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> judge issued an injunction stopping the state from enforcing it. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>'s ruling encouraged <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Orleans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> Attorney <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Connick </PERSON> to ask a federal court judge to lift the injunction. His request has enraged abortion rights activists. `` <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> is a major battleground,'' said <PERSON> Shirley </PERSON> <PERSON> Pedler </PERSON>, director of the local chapter of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberties </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>. `` It is the first state to try to criminalize abortion, even without grounds to do so.'' In <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION>, brthplace of the latest round in the abortion struggle, Gov. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Ashcroft </PERSON> announced plans the day of the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling to appoint a task force to explore ways of further restricting abortions. Other states are convening committees and beginning political dialogue that is intended to reach some sort of consensus on abortion. <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Branstad </PERSON> said he would ask the Legislature for restrictions on abortion, but wanted to `` consult with a broad range of Iowans'' first. In <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Minority Leader <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> <PERSON> Webster </PERSON> announced formation of a <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> committee to study the issue. And in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, Assembly Speaker <PERSON> Chuck </PERSON> <PERSON> Hardwick </PERSON> said he will launch `` the great debate'' in September by convening a committee of the entire 80-member Assembly to question witnesses and consider bills on abortion. <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Clements </PERSON>, who is against abortion, said he probably would ask the Legislature to consider abortion restrictions if another special session is held later this year. In <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, Gov. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> said he would call a special session of the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> in October to consider abortion bills. `` Clearly, I believe the unborn ought to have more rights than they have right now,'' <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> said. `` I do n't believe we ought to wait until 1990 to deal with a difficult subject. It's not something that's going to go away.''
