<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An Italian company rumored to be trying to corner the soybean market has asked a federal judge to block a <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> order that would force it to sell a huge quantity of soybean futures. The lawsuit filed Thursday by <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trading </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> SA </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> USA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, both subsidiaries of <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finanziara </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> SpA </ORGANIZATION>, seeks a temporary restraining order and a permanent injunction against the exchange's directive. The suit claims <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> had been irreparably injured by the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>'s order and says the directive would diminish confidence in the market and hurt <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> farmers.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> BAT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION> has abandoned a $ 400 million note issue because of what it called market disruption caused by a hostile $ 21 billion takeover bid from an investor group led by Sir <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldsmith </PERSON>. The issue, set for completion Monday, would have been one of the biggest Eurobond offerings ever by a non-U.S. company. The London-based conglomerate said it withdrew the issue Thursday to protect investors against substantial possible losses from `` the hostile and highly leveraged nature of the bid.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A House-Senate conference trying to craft a savings and loan bailout bill deadlocked in procedural limbo after <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> negotiators proposed a comprehensive compromise. The leader of the five-member <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> team suprised many <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> members Thursday by delivering an outline of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> proposal and asking them to consider it overnight. But the 94-member <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> delegation has been unable to respond because its leader has divided the delegation into platoons of 20 or 30 members, each with jurisdiction over part of the bill. House delegates voted to put the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> offer aside and proceeded to try to tackle the massive S & amp; L bill issue by issue.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Early-July sales of North American-made cars and light trucks jumped 8.9 percent over the same period last year, the companies report. The eight major U.S.-based automakers reported Thursday that they sold vehicles at an average rate of 35,614 a day during the July 1-10 period this year compared with a rate of 32,696 during the same time last year. Car sales were up 9.3 percent and truck sales rose 8.3 percent.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The annual economic summit meeting will be dominated by environmental pollution and <LOCATION> East-West </LOCATION> relations because, this year, there's little bad economic news for the seven participants to discuss. President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and the leaders of the six other large, industrialized western democracies will meet today through Sunday. Along the way, they will take time for lavish dinners, fireworks displays and festive parades organized by French President <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> to commemorate the 200th anniversary of the French Revolution.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Anglo-Dutch consumer products giant <ORGANIZATION> Unilever </ORGANIZATION> will acquire the Faberge and <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Arden </PERSON> lines of toiletries, cosmetics and fragrances for $ 1.55 billion, salvaging a deal that had been abandoned in April, it was announced. A definitive contract between <PERSON> Faberge </PERSON>'s owner, <ORGANIZATION> Riklis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Family </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> Unilever </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> States </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the holding company for <ORGANIZATION> Unilever </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> operations, has been signed and the transaction is expected to be completed within 30 days, according to Thursday's announcement
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Lawyers seeking to represent more than 80,000 people have filed suit against the investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and leveraged buyout specialist <ORGANIZATION> Kohlberg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kravis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Roberts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> seeking to reverse the $ 2.4 billion takeover of <ORGANIZATION> Jim </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Walter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> two years ago. The lawsuit, filed Thursday in state court in <LOCATION> Beaumont </LOCATION>, claims the buyout was a fraudulent attempt to escape more than $ 3 billion in liabilities stemming from asbestos claims against <ORGANIZATION> Celotex </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, a subsidiary of <LOCATION> Tampa </LOCATION>, Fla.-based home-builder <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Walter </PERSON>, also named as a defendant. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> last year sold <ORGANIZATION> Celotex </ORGANIZATION>, a long-time producer of asbestos, which has been linked to cancer and other health problems.
