<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The suspense over the future of <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> continued as <ORGANIZATION> Delaware </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chancery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Judge <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> did not issue a ruling in <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>'s bid to stop <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION>'s planned merger with <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> was expected to rule by the end of the week, but a clerk at the <LOCATION> Wilmington </LOCATION>, court said the judge would not announce a decision Thursday. The judge conferred with lawyers for both sides by telephone but the subject of their discussions was not known.
