<SECOND>PM-Computer Conference,0275</SECOND>
<HEAD>Conference Kicks Off 2-Year Project</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 As much as 10 percent of the world's gross national product may be spent on computers and computer-related equipment by the year 2000, says the chairman of a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> telecommunications subcommittee. Rep. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Markey </PERSON>, D-Mass., said Thursday at a <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> conference launching a two-year project by the <ORGANIZATION> Congressional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> for the Future that computers will become an integral part of human life `` Retail products, financial services, health care, basic research and development, basic education, worker retraining and even prison security _ all of these areas of service could be revolutionized by coming changes in information industries,'' said <PERSON> Markey </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on telecommunications and finance. The project, `` Challenging the Information Age,'' is being undertaken by the non-profit educational organization that involves members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, industry executives and other private-sector policy leaders. Thursday's conference included demonstrations of high-tech products, including a supercomputer, interactive videodisc systems for storage and rapid retrieval of massive amounts of data, and electronic networks to provide information to schools and individuals. `` The future implications of issues and choices to be examined by the institute's information age project are enormous,'' <PERSON> Markey </PERSON> said. `` Forecasters suggest that in the year 2000, 8 to 10 percent of the world's GNP will be expended on telecommunications products and hardware.'' <PERSON> Markey </PERSON> said industrialized nations, including <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, will battle for the lion's share of the market. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, he said, already is predicting that telecommunications products soon will make up a fifth of its GNP.
</TEXT>
