<SECOND>PM-Wall Street Rebound, Bjt,0722</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brokerages Expected To Post Strong Quarter As Retail Activity Up</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Declining interest rates and increased stock activity have boosted activity at Wall Street's investment houses, which have struggled in an industrywide recession that has included layoffs and restructuring. Much of the renewed optimism, which should be reflected in improved second-quarter profits at major brokerages, is based on a return of individual investors to a stock market tarnished by the October 1987 crash. `` We see much more interest in individual securities, whether stocks or bonds, which obviously would bode well for the industry,'' <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Markese </PERSON>, research director for the 110,000-member <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Individual </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investors </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, said Thursday. A rise in June in merger activity and in fees generated by underwriting new issues of stocks and bonds _ two key indicators of <LOCATION> Wall </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Street </LOCATION>'s health _ should lift industry profits compared with the first quarter, when some firms lost money, analysts said. `` Without a doubt it's going to be one of the better quarters for the industry,'' said <PERSON> Brenda </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> <PERSON> McCoy </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> PaineWebber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Salomon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, parent of <LOCATION> Salomon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bros. </LOCATION>, earlier this week announced that its second-quarter earnings would be the company's best ever, exceeding the $ 190 million earned in the first quarter of <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gutfreund </PERSON>, <PERSON> Salomon </PERSON>'s chairman and chief executive, said the first half of 1989 for the firm would be `` only modestly below'' that of first-half 1988, when it made $ 253 million, or $ 1.68 a share, on revenue of $ 3.04 billion. Earnings forecasts for other firms also are optimistic: 40 cents to 50 cents a share for <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, compared with 31 cents a share in the first quarter; $ 2.60 a share for <ORGANIZATION> Morgan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stanley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, up from $ 2.02 for January to March; and about 50 cents a share for <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Holdings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> after nine months of losses. But analysts caution that profit levels are n't even close to the boom times that preceded the stock market crash and say many of the factors that led to thousands of layoffs and retrenchment on Wall Street remain. `` You ca n't just throw up your hands and say we've turned,'' said <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Eckenfelder </PERSON>, a securities industry analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Prudential </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` We may still be in a recession three months from now on the Street.'' The expected improved results are being attributed to a steady decline in short-term interest rates that has prompted some investors to transfer money from money market funds and bank certificates of deposit to investments with higher returns, generating more trading profit for the firms. For instance, the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>'s one-year bill had a yield of 8.10 percent at the end of June compared with 9.58 percent at the end of March. Some money market interest rates, which fetched over 10 percent earlier this year, recently dipped below 8 percent. Declining interest rates mean investment banks pay less to borrow money to finance inventories of fixed-income securities. Also, brokerages typically receive much higher commissions on investment vehicles other than CDs and money markets, including retail trades. Higher stock trading volume also means more commission business. The <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION>'s average daily volume in June was 180.3 million, the highest in a year and third-highest in any month since October 1987. Merger and acquisitions and securities underwriting activity both jumped in June, providing additional fuel to the strong quarter, statistics show. The total value of announced acquisitions in June was $ 37.7 billion, the second-best month this year, according to <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, which tracks industry data. Analysts forecast a continued rise in merger activity if interest rates stay down. Fees generated from initial public offerings of stock _ considered a sign of companies' confidence in whether investors are buying stock _ totaled $ 1.63 billion in June, up from $ 261 million in April, <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> reported. But the industry is n't in clover yet. `` I do n't think the public is yet of the psychology or philosophy that they are going to miss something big and are ready to jump into the stock market,'' said <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Barbanel </PERSON>, a senior vice president of <ORGANIZATION> Gruntal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a midsized <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> investment firm.
</TEXT>
