<SECOND>BCBritain-Inflation,0225</SECOND>
<HEAD>Annual Rate Holds Steady at 8.3 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>' a annual inflation rate held steady at 8.3 percent in June, and may have reached its peak, the government announced Friday. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s retail price index rose 0.3 percent in June from May, the Department of Employment said Friday. Market forecasts had called for a 0.5 percent gain. The index, which uses a January 1987 base of 100, stood at 115.4 in June, compared with 115 in May and 106.6 in June 1988. `` Inflation may now have reached its peak,'' said Employment Secretary <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> <PERSON> Fowler </PERSON>. `` It is set to fall as the measures taken by the chancellor begin to work through.'' Chancellor of the Exchequer <PERSON> Nigel </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> has pushed up interest rates 10 times _ to 14 percent from 7.5 percent a year ago _ in an effort to combat <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s resurgent inflation. The annual inflation rate stood at 4.6 percent in June 1988. If mortgage interest payments were excluded, the latest inflation rate would have been 5.9 percent in June, <PERSON> Folower </PERSON> said, This compared with May's 6-percent rate, excluding such payments. The June rise in the index reflected higher prices for food, catering, alcoholic drinks and motor vehicles, the department said. The increase also reflected a continuing rise in housing costs, it said.
