<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, eager to score an initial victory for its strategy to reduce Third World debt, has offered <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> a temporary loan of $ 1 billion to $ 2 billion to help it close lengthy negotiations with commercial bankers. White House Chief of Staff <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON> said today that <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and its commercial lenders have some sticky issues to resolve and that no deal was in sight. `` The quality of the solution is more important than the timetable,'' <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON> told reporters a few hours before the economic summit of seven major industrial democracies opened here. Mexican officials, he said, want to `` get it done correctly rather than trying to rush it.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> held a hastily arranged meeting this morning with Mexican President <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gortari </PERSON>, who is attending festivities marking the 200th anniversary of the French Revolution. <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> also has met with some other summit leaders. <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, the test case in the new <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> approach to the Third World's $ 1.3 trillion debt problem, has been holding closely watched discussions with its commercial bankers to try to restructure its portfolio of foreign loans. <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON> said Mexican and bank negotiators were `` very close'' on terms for an agreement but that they had been stuck on a few key points for almost a week. <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON> confirmed a report in today's editions of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> that to sweeten the prospective deal, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has offered to make a so-called bridge loan to <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> of $ 1 billion to $ 2 billion. `` We are ready to do that if it is what is necessary in order to complete the agreement ...,'' he said. <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> has received similar <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> loans in the past to ease its financial difficulties until fresh assistance from commerical banks became available. A bridge loan is considered an inducement for bankers to make a deal because the new money allows a debtor nation to continue meeting its interest payments on foreign loans. A little more than half of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s total foreign debt is owed to commercial bankers, many of them American institutions. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would like to wrap a deal as soon as possible to show its summit partners that its new approach on the debt, drawn up by <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON>, can work. But <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON> emphasized that `` there is no requirement to leave the summit ... with an agreement'' and that an artificial deadline might hurt the quality of the final agreement. Walking into the meeting with <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> gestured to reporters that a debt agreement was near. Afterward, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> told his Mexican counterpart, `` Let me know on all this other stuff down the road.'' The Bush-Salinas meeting came as more than two dozen leaders of rich and poor nations marked today's 200th anniversary of the French revolution. Getting under way this afternoon was the annual economic summit of the world's seven richest democracies _ the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. The combined events have brought together leaders of some of the world's richest and poorest nations, although there were no plans for them all to sit down together to thrash out world problems. Smaller meetings were planned, however, to discuss such pressing issues as the foreign debt of the developing nations. <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Senegal </LOCATION> wasted no time Thursday in asking French President <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> to call a summit of rich and poor nations so they can talk about international economic and environmental problems. Brazilian President <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON> also has pressed his country's case with foreign officials <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> are the developing world's two biggest debtors, with combined foreign loans of more than $ 200 billion. <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> met Thursday with <LOCATION> Japanese </LOCATION> Prime Minister <PERSON> Sousuke </PERSON> <PERSON> Uno </PERSON> and West German Chancellor <PERSON> Helmut </PERSON> <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON>, a day after talks with Canadian Prime Minister <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON>. <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>' southern neighbor, has often led efforts to bring an end to the Third World debt crisis, which dates to 1982 when that country was unable to meet its loan payments. <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> met informally with <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON> to discuss debt rescheduling and the <LOCATION> German </LOCATION> leader's ideas for `` debt for nature'' swaps, according to <LOCATION> German </LOCATION> government spokesman <PERSON> Hans </PERSON> <PERSON> Klein </PERSON>. Under a swap arrangement, some foreign loans would be forgiven in exchange for promises of environmental protection. At the economic summit, Uno plans to pledge nearly $ 40 billion for debt relief and environmental aid for developing nations, according to a <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> official, who earlier in the week briefed reporters in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> on condition of anonymity. He wants to increase <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s `` recycling of funds'' program for the debtor nations by $ 35 billion, which will include $ 5.5 billion for the <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> plan. The recycling of money refers to the government's effort to use capital from its trade surplus to help poorer nations. In addition, $ 2.25 billion will be set aside for projects to preserve the environment and study environmental problems.
