<HEAD>Guinness To Pay Distillers Holders Another 85 Million Pounds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 British brewer <ORGANIZATION> Guinness </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION> will pay an extra 85 million pounds, or $ 138 million, to former <ORGANIZATION> Distillers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> shareholders to settle a dispute stemming from its takeover of the liquor company, the <ORGANIZATION> Panel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> On </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Takeovers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mergers </ORGANIZATION> said Friday. Guinness acquired Distillers for 2.53 billion pounds, or $ 4.1 billion, in 1986. The takeover panel, a self-regulatory body which oversees bids involving British companies, said <ORGANIZATION> Guinness </ORGANIZATION> would pay the difference between its official 630.3-pence a share, or $ 10.21, offer to <ORGANIZATION> Distillers </ORGANIZATION>' shareholders and the 731 pence per share which <ORGANIZATION> Guinness </ORGANIZATION> paid separately for shares through a Swiss company acting on its behalf. The purchases made at the higher price were found by the takeover panel to be in breach of British regulations. They and a number of other alleged irregularities have become known as the `` Guinness affair.'' Seven men involved in the takeover, including then-chairman <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON> <PERSON> Saunders </PERSON>, face trial on criminal charges related to the case. The payments to shareholders are `` in the best interests of the company and its shareholders,'' <ORGANIZATION> Guinness </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Tennant </PERSON> said. The panel said that <ORGANIZATION> Distillers </ORGANIZATION> shareholders who had accepted <ORGANIZATION> Guinness </ORGANIZATION>' cash offer would be paid another 100.7 pence a share plus interest charges of 10 percent a year. Compensation also will be paid to <ORGANIZATION> Distillers </ORGANIZATION> shareholders who acquired <ORGANIZATION> Guinness </ORGANIZATION> shares in accepting <ORGANIZATION> Guinness </ORGANIZATION>' alternative cash-and-shares offer and sold them prior to the official completion of the bid. <ORGANIZATION> Distillers </ORGANIZATION> shareholders who did n't accept either offer yet sold their Distillers shares for less than 731 pence before the official completion of the bid would also be compensated, the panel said. The panel said <ORGANIZATION> Guinness </ORGANIZATION> estimated the cost of the compensation could total as much as 85 million pounds.
