<FIRST>r f PM-LogCabins     07-14 0649</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Log Cabins,0670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Log Cabins Become Popular Again _ Here And Abroad</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The descendants of the log cabins of the American frontier are gaining popularity in <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, as well as at home. Not the rough-hewn logs and mud-floored types of yore, though. These are the modern, sleek versions _ made of precisely cut pieces of wood and coming equipped with modern conveniences, including jacuzzis and saunas. And the increasing popularity of log homes, both at home and abroad, could pep up north <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>'s forest products industry, said <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahaffey </PERSON>, president of Fireside Log Homes in <LOCATION> Ellijay </LOCATION>, one of 14 log home makers in <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> and one of the nation's largest. Last year, Fireside produced 250 log homes, ranging in price from $ 19,600 to $ 42,800. And Mahaffey estimates that exports of the log homes could make up as much as half of Fireside's volume by 1992. According to Log Home Living, a magazine that tracks the industry, 452 American log homes were exported last year, including 390 to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. Overall, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> industry's 466 manufacturers produced about 14,353 homes last year, 2,533 fewer than in 1987. Sales by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> manufacturers increased to $ 413.4 million in 1988 from $ 401 million in 1987, the magazine said. <PERSON> Mahaffey </PERSON> leaves next week for <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> to unveil a 1,000-square-foot log home that Fireside developed especially for the Japanese market. `` The Japanese are fascinated with solid-wood-wall construction,'' said <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>, program director of the <ORGANIZATION> Building </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Builders </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION> `` For one thing, wood is very scarce in that country. Apparently, it's a status symbol.'' But <PERSON> Mahaffey </PERSON> said many Americans still perceive log homes to be drafty fire hazards that are susceptible to termites. The industry is trying to change that image. Officials say log homes, because they are built of solid wood, are able to retard fires better than conventionally built houses. And a log home's thick walls provide better insulation and thus are more energy efficient, they say Many of today's log homes are built from machine-made kits, although a few are still handcrafted. But <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Kupferer </PERSON>, editor and publisher of Log Home Living, warns buyers that all log homes require more maintenance than conventional houses in the first two years after construction. `` Until this whole mass of wood settles and shrinks and acclimates itself, you need to keep the exterior maintained with a preservative, and you need to keep the cracks filled, otherwise they fill with moisture,'' he said. <PERSON> Kupferer </PERSON> said the industry is selling larger houses. He noted that the domestic log-home market is shifting from first-time home buyers to existing homeowners moving up to larger residences. `` In the late 1970s and early'80s, we built a lot more houses than we do today,'' said <PERSON> Dewey </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON>, sales manager at <ORGANIZATION> Mountaineer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Log </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Homes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Baldwin </LOCATION>, which now produces about 50 homes a year, most of them custom-made. `` There was a tremendous amount of small cabins then. But we have gone from the secondary home to the primary residence.'' Where the typical Mountaineer home once was 800 to 1,200 square feet, it now is 1,500 to 5,000 square feet, <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> said. `` We just finished one that is 6,700 square feet down in <LOCATION> Snellville </LOCATION>,'' he said. `` I like wood, I like wood interiors,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Massey </PERSON>, 68, former president of the <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cobb </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION>. He owns a 1,680-square-foot, three-bedroom, two - bath log home on Walnut Mountain near <LOCATION> Ellijay </LOCATION> `` A log home breathes,'' <PERSON> Massey </PERSON> said, `` and you get better circulation and better and even temperatures in a log home.'' According to Log Home Living's latest survey, most log home owners are middle-aged, college-educated professionals who have at least two children. About 43 percent have annual incomes of more than $ 40,000. Some 84 percent use their log homes, which average 1,872 square feet, as their primary residence.
