<FIRST>u f PM-WholesalesPrices 3rdLd-Writethru f0047 07-14 0860</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wholesales Prices, 3rd Ld-Writethru, f0047,0882</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wholesale Prices Post First Decline in 18 Months</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Retransmitting to correct that this is 3rd Ld-Writethru; ^Inserts
graf 4, And the Federal Reserve, with report on factory operating rate
and industrial production.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Wholesale prices fell 0.1 percent in June, the first drop in 18 months, driven down by steep declines in energy and food prices, the government said today. The slight decline in the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s Producer Price Index surprised most economists, who were expecting a moderate increase of 0.3 percent, and marked a sharp turnaround from the big 0.9 percent jump in May. In another report, the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said retail sales fell 0.4 percent in June _ their first monthly back-to-back drop in more than two years _ as consumer spending remained sluggish, particularly for cars and other more costly durable goods. And the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> reported the operating rate for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> factories fell in June to 83.5 percent, while industrial production dropped 0.2 percent, further easing concerns about inflation but providing more evidence of a slowing economy. Energy costs, which had soared more than 20 percent over the first five months of the year, fell 3.1 percent in June, the biggest drop in three years. Food prices fell 0.8 percent, the steepest in a year and a half, reversing an identical increase in May. Despite the overall decline, economists were likely to read mixed signals from the June report because goods other than food and energy rose 0.7 percent, the largest increase since October 1986. Because food and energy prices swing widely from month to month and are less influenced by the economy as a whole, analysts look to the inflation rate of other goods as an indicator of underlying inflationary pressures in the economy. Despite the drop in the index last month, wholesale inflation for the first half of 1989 hit a fast 7.6 percent annual pace, nearly double last year's 4 percent rise. The <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said prices of tomatoes and celery, which had doubled in May, fell sharply in June. Vegetables overall fell 8 percent last month, following a 26.4 percent rise in May. Other food catagories posting declines in May were: pasta, 9 percent; fish, 7.3 percent; chickens, 5.2 percent, and beef and veal, 3.8 percent. Prices rose for pork, <LOCATION> turkey </LOCATION>, fresh fruit, eggs and candy. Energy costs fell across the board with drops of 8 percent for fuel oil, 4 percent for gasoline and 2 percent for natural gas. The department said the increase in other categories was driven primarily by a 5.8 percent jump in cigarettes and other tobacco products and for ships. Prices for prescription and over-the-counter drugs, soaps and furniture also rose, while prices for flatware, women's clothing, jewelry, glassware and cosmetics declined. The overall June decline left the Producer Price Index for finished goods one stop short of retail at 114.1, meaning that a hypothetical selection of goods costing $ 100 in 1982 would have cost $ 114.10 last month, 10 cents less than in May but $ 6.40 more than a year ago. The news from inflation measures earlier in the production process was also good. The price of intermediate goods fell 0.2 percent in June after rising only 0.1 percent in May, while crude goods dropped 2.0 percent following a 0.9 percent rise. An example of the three processing stages would be finished _ bread; intermediate _ flour and crude _ wheat. Most economists believe inflation will continue to moderate over the next several months, but they're divided over the long-term outlook. Analysts point out that much of the price spurt earlier this year was fueled by a once-and-done run-up in crude oil prices in the spring. Now that oil has stabilized at the $ 20-a-barrel level, energy prices should n't be contributing to inflation for a while, they believe. Also, even though food prices have jumped around a bit this year, it is clear there will be no repeat of last year's drought in most of the nation's grain-growing regions. `` Therefore, the PPI should remain relatively well-behaved over the next several months,'' predicts economist <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Ratajczak </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. Between March 1988 and March of this year, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> fought to curb demand, and thus inflation, by boosting interest rates. However, the economy has clearly slowed so far this year and the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> has permitted interest rates to decline. Early in June and again last week, the central bank nudged a key interest rate, the rate banks charge each other for overnight loans, down by a quarter of a percentage point. Economist <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Berson </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mortgage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> said in advance of today's report that if inflation turned out to have moderated last month and if other government reports today on retail sales and industrial activity in June confirmed the slowing trend, <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> policymakers might be inclined to ease credit another notch before the end of the month. `` I think the chances of getting another easing are good. But, just as the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> was cautious in going up, they're going to be cautious in coming down,'' <PERSON> Berson </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
