<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration has offered <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> a temporary loan of $ 1 billion to $ 2 billion to help bring to a close an agreement with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> banks on debt restructuring, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials said today. White House Chief of Staff <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Mexican </LOCATION> and bank negotiators were `` very close'' on terms for an agreement. The loan is contingent on an accord between the country and its creditors to reduce and rearrange $ 54 billion in existing loans. However, some outstanding issues remain and no deal is in sight, <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON> said. `` The quality of the solution is more important than the timetable,'' the White House official told reporters a few hours before the opening of the economic summit here. According to <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON>, Mexican officials want to `` get it done correctly rather than trying to rush it.'' The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> reported in today's editions that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> sought to sweeten such a deal between <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and the banks by providing a so-called bridge loan. `` We are ready to do that if it is what is necessary in order to complete the agreement ...,'' <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON> said in confirming the report. President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> met this morning with with Mexican President <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gortari </PERSON>. The two are attending the 200th anniversary celebration of the French Revolution. Such loans are sometimes used to assist a country hampered by paperwork delays following debtor loan negotiations with foreign bank creditors. More than half of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s total foreign debt is owed to commercial banks, many of them in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The Mexican government has said it would want to reach such an agreement before accepting new loans. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has indicated it would like to wrap up an accord as soon as possible, a sign to the other summit nations that it has adopted a new approach on the debt. <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON> stressed that `` there is no requirement to leave the summit ... with an agreement'' and that an artificial deadline might hurt the quality of the final agreement.
