<SECOND>BC-Credit Markets, Adv 17,0756</SECOND>
<HEAD>adv17</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday, July 17</HEAD>
<HEAD>Peril of `Junk' Commercial Paper Shown By Integrated Resources' Default</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BART ZIEGLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 As if junk bonds were n't enough for investors to worry about, now the spotlight has been turned on yet another high-risk, high-yield security: junk commercial paper. The perils of this form of corporate debt were pointed out recently by the collapse of <ORGANIZATION> Integrated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a real estate and investment company that defaulted on $ 955 million in short-term obligations, including its commercial paper. Complicating matters is that <ORGANIZATION> Integrated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resource </ORGANIZATION>'s commercial paper was not rated as junk, or high-risk, until after the company's financial problems came to light last month That means investors saw their investment-grade Integrated Resources commercial paper turn into junk in a matter of days. However, most small investors have little to worry about. Their only exposure to commercial paper would be through mutual funds and pension funds, and the risk to these investments is small, experts say. One type of mutual fund, money-market funds, invest in large amounts of investment-grade commercial paper, but most are barred by federal law from purchasing low-rated commercial paper. The major mutual fund operators do their own credit analysis before they make any investment, said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Lipper </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Lipper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Analytical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which tracks the mutual-fund industry. That kind of examination keeps Integrated Resources paper out of the portfolios of most of the largest fund operators, including <ORGANIZATION> Fidelity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investments </ORGANIZATION>, The <ORGANIZATION> Vanguard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Kemper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Companies </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> T. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rowe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Price </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. These fund operators said Integrated Resources never met their investment standards despite its acceptable ratings from the credit rating agencies. `` We would n't have even considered it,'' said <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Norwitz </PERSON>, a Price vice president. `` It had been in a negative cash-flow situation for years.'' One exception is <ORGANIZATION> Value </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Line </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a mutual fund operator that held <ORGANIZATION> Integrated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> paper in one of its money market funds. Value Line said the investment represented about 3.8 percent of the fund's net assets. Market professionals have placed the amount at $ 22 million to $ 24 million; <ORGANIZATION> Value </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Line </ORGANIZATION> would not reveal the figure. Value Line said last week that it had bought the paper from the fund, which eliminated it as a risk to the fund's investors. <ORGANIZATION> Lipper </ORGANIZATION> said he believes other funds had invested in Integrated Resources paper, but <ORGANIZATION> Value </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Line </ORGANIZATION> has been the only one to publicly acknowledge it. <ORGANIZATION> Fidelity </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Vanguard </ORGANIZATION> and Price, among others, also said they never invest in junk commercial paper for any of their mutual funds. Junk commercial paper is a small subset of the $ 450 billion commercial paper market, used by companies to raise cash for short-term needs. Commercial paper with investment-grade ratings is considered a relatively safe investment. Companies issuing it usually have high ratings on all their debt obligations due to their strong financial positions. Commercial paper is a form of short-term corporate IOU usually not secured by assets, though it is supposed to be backed by bank lines of credit. Companies sell the paper to raise money for periods ranging from a few days to a few months. The reasons for issuing commercial paper vary. Some companies use it to tide them over until proceeds from a bond issue arrive. Others use it for working capital or to provide cash until funds from regular operations come in. Companies find commercial paper attractive because the interest rates they must pay on it usually are lower than bank-loan rates. Commercial paper also provides flexibility in the length of the loan. Junk commercial paper, by contrast, is issued by companies that are deep in debt or have low debt ratings for other reasons. Its yield is higher than investment-grade paper because of the added risk to investors. The safety of the investment-grade commercial paper market is reflected by its history. Only one issue has defaulted since the early 1970s, said <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> McQuire </PERSON>, an executive vice president at <ORGANIZATION> Moody </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. That issue was <ORGANIZATION> Manville </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which filed for bankruptcy-court protection over asbestos-related lawsuits. <PERSON> McQuire </PERSON> said he did not have figures on the number of junk-paper issues that have defaulted. But while the track record of investment-grade paper is excellent, the Integrated Resources case shows it is not a foolproof place to put money.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Monday, July 17</NOTE>
