<HEAD>House Drops Objections to Looking At Broad Senate Bailout Proposal</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: LEADS with 15 grafs to UPDATE with action today; picks up 9th
graf pvs, bgng: `Treasury Secretary'; DELETES last 2 grafs. ^LaserPhoto
WX8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> House-Senate </ORGANIZATION> conferees today said they had unsnarled a procedural knot that had threatened to stall a $ 157 billion taxpayer bailout of savings and loan losses. After balking Thursday night at a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> offer of a comprehensive package addressing major differences in <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> versions of the legislation, the chief <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> negotiator, Rep. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, agreed today to several of its provisions. <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, reviewed a broad outline of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> proposal overnight. Today he said the two sides are `` so close on an overwhelming majority'' of issues that he will draft a counterproposal on behalf of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>. `` ` My intention is to provide a starting point for an overall settlement,'' he told the five <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> negotiators. `` I believe this provides the basis for us to resolve the impasse.'' But <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON> and Sen. <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Riegle </PERSON>, D-Mich., the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s chief negotiator as chairman of its banking committee, acknowledged that the two sides remain far apart on one issue: how to finance the bailout Nonetheless, both expressed optimism today that enough of an agreement could be reached by the middle of next week to have a bill ready for President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s signature in August. To minimize the bailout's impact on the federal deficit, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> want to raise the $ 50 billion immediately needed to close some 500 insolvent S & amp; Ls and cover the losses of their depositors through private 30-year bonds. Citing potential interest savings totaling $ 4.5 billion over 30 years, the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> has demanded that the money be borrowed directly through the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>, a move that would swell the deficit by a total of $ 44 billion in fiscal 1989, 1990 and 1991. `` That will remain the key outstanding issue to be debated,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Jake </PERSON> <PERSON> Garn </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>, the ranking <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> conferee. In the meantime, <PERSON> Garn </PERSON> agreed to proceed with negotiations today on how much new capital the government should require S & amp; L owners to invest in their businesses as a buffer against future losses of federally insured deposits. `` We're not very far apart,'' he said. <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON> said he was prepared to accept several provisions in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> bill that impose tougher regulatory requirements on some S & amp; L operations, and he was willing offer compromises on others. Earlier, he had described the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s offer as `` aggravating'' and a `` horrendous injustice'' to a previous agreement to consider hundreds of differences between the two bills item by item. Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Heinz </PERSON>, R-Pa., said that step-by-step approach would `` take until Christmas'' to get a bill acceptable to both the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> as well as the administration `` It's to the advantage of all concerned to open the deck and put all 52 cards on the table face up,'' <PERSON> Heinz </PERSON> said. Treasury Secretary <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> issued a statement from <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> saying the administration would `` strongly support'' the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> offer, but wanted to review its details. Administration officials, meanwhile, worked furiously behind the scenes Thursday night to prevent votes on specific issues. The dispute brought to the surface major procedural differences in the way the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> have addressed the S & amp; L crisis and the bailout _ the largest in history, with an estimated cost of $ 1,000 to $ 1,500 per taxpayer. Both <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON> and <PERSON> Riegle </PERSON> are new to their respective banking committee chairmanships. <PERSON> Riegle </PERSON>'s 21-member <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> committee met behind closed doors last spring, negotiating compromises on most issues _ including several provisions to benefit specific companies _ before voting on it in public as a package. <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON> had his 51-member panel put the House version together entirely in open sessions. He called the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> offer Thursday an attempt to avoid taking stands on specific items in the package that might offend industry and other constituencies. `` For the first time, there is a spotlight on them, everybody is watching, and they're not used to that,'' <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON> said. `` They're used to getting behind closed doors and cutting deals, but that's where all the mischief has been Among other key elements of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> offer are: _ Acceptance of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>'s plan to require S & amp; L owners to risk $ 3 in real, tangible capital for every $ 100 in lending by Jan. 1, 1995 The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> bill had provided a laxer standard of $ 1.50. _ A compromise limiting <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; L ownership of junk bonds to 6 percent of their assets The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> had wanted to require S & amp; Ls to sell their junk bonds within two years, while the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> bill has a more liberal junk bond limit of 11 percent of assets. _ Adoption of a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> clause guaranteeing <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Danny </PERSON> <PERSON> Wall </PERSON> the right to keep his job for the next two years and retain his authority over state-chartered S & amp; Ls
