<HEAD>Class-action Suit Filed, Alleging Owners Not Given Adequate Warnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Credit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> employees violated state law by repossessing up to 1,300 cars and trucks without giving owners adequate warning that they missed their payments, a lawsuit contends. The class-action lawsuit filed by the state consumer advocate charges that <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Credit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> employees ignored a state law that requires written notice explaining to a car or truck owner that he has a 20-day grace period to make good on a missed payment before the vehicle is repossessed. Vehicles were sometimes repossessed with little more than a telephone call to warn owners that they missed payments, state Consumer Advocate <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamm </PERSON> said in his suit filed Thursday in <ORGANIZATION> Richland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. The suit also alleges that employees of the Detroit-based finance company deliberately flouted the consumer-protection law and sometimes faked office records to make it appear that they had not. <PERSON> Hamm </PERSON> said it appeared that the consumer-protection law was skirted so employees could cut down on paperwork. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Credit </ORGANIZATION> is investigating the allegations and will cooperate, a spokesman said. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Heath </PERSON> said the company contacted <PERSON> Hamm </PERSON>'s office after an employee in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> complained in May about the way some repossessions were being handled The lawsuit asks that a judge forbid <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Credit </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> employees from continuing to break the consumer-protection law, even though <PERSON> Heath </PERSON> said the company has stopped the violations. The lawsuit also seeks some kind of `` adjustment'' for the owners of the 1,200 to 1,300 vehicles that <PERSON> Hamm </PERSON> claims were illegally repossessed over the last five or six years. <PERSON> Hamm </PERSON> said he did not know what form the `` adjustment'' would take. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Credit </ORGANIZATION> will `` do whatever we have to do to try to reach a fair and equitable settlement,'' <PERSON> Heath </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Credit </ORGANIZATION> has offices in <LOCATION> Richland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Greenville </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION> counties, but <PERSON> Hamm </PERSON> and <PERSON> Heath </PERSON> said the problems were centered in the <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> office.
