<HEAD>U.S. to Lift Punitive Fee on European Hams</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is lifting its punitive 100 percent tariff on bone-in hams from the 12 <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> nations because they have allowed the shipment of some <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> meat not treated with hormones, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Trade Representative <PERSON> Carla </PERSON> <PERSON> Hills </PERSON> said Friday. The amount involved is small _ the Europeans have been shipping only about $ 300,000 worth of the hams annually _ but it is an easing of a conflict between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the community over hormones in meat. The move followed the acceptance by the community of a small quantity of veal offals -LRB- variety meats -RRB- from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. `` We continue to believe that the <ORGANIZATION> EC </ORGANIZATION>'s ban on meat produced with hormones is entirely unjustified,'' Ms. <PERSON> Hills </PERSON> said in a statement. The community banned from Jan. 1 the sale of meat from animals treated with hormones to fatten them. In retaliation, the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration imposed an extra 100 percent tariff on European shipments to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> of products with a value roughly equivalent to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> meat exports halted by the ban. One of the products was bone-in ham. A joint European-American task force agreed in May on shipping <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> meat not treated with hormones, and to reduce <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> retaliation to the extent that American meat could be sold.
