<HEAD>Retail Sales Plummet in June</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: To reflect Commerce Department CORRECTION, make lead read first
monthly back-to-back drop in nearly two years, and change 3rd graf to read
first consecutive monthly decline since 1987.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Retail sales fell 0.4 percent in June _ their first monthly back-to-back drop in nearly two years _ as consumer spending remained sluggish, particularly for cars and other more costly durable goods, the government reported today. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said sales dropped to a seasonally adjusted $ 140.8 billion last month following a 0.1 percent decline in May. The May figure was revised downward from an 0.1 percent increase originally reported last month. Sales had risen 0.4 percent in April and 0.1 percent in March. It was the first consecutive monthly decline since 1987 when sales fell 0.8 percent in September and 0.9 percent in October. Retail spending accounts for about one-third of economic activity and is closely watched as a measure of the overall economy. Economic growth has been slowing recently, prompting concern that <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> efforts to contain inflation could move the economy into a recession instead of the `` soft-landing'' it seeks. Spending on durable goods _ big ticket items such as cars and home appliances that are expected to last more than three years _ has been particularly affected by the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>'s credit-tightening measures. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said durable goods sales were off 1.3 percent in June after falling 0.5 percent in May and rising 1.8 percent in April. Auto sales plummeted 2.0 percent in June after falling 1.8 percent in May. It was the biggest drop in auto sales since a 4 percent decline in October 1987. Sales had risen 2.0 percent in April _ a month of large dealer incentives. Autos represent about 20 percent of total retail sales. Excluding the automotive category, overall retail sales rose 0.1 percent, following hikes of 0.4 percent in May and 1.2 percent in April. Sales of home furnishings fell 0.1 percent after rising 1.1 percent in May. Sales of non-durable goods rose 0.2 percent last month, the same increase as in May. They had risen 0.6 percent in April. Department store and other general merchandise spending was up 2.1 percent. Also showing increased sales in the non-durable category was apparel sales, up 1.9 percent. Non-durable categories posting declines included: food stores, down 0.7 percent; gasoline stations, down 0.5 percent; restaurants and bars, down 0.2 percent and drug stores, off 0.3 percent. For the three months from April through June, overall retail sales were up 5.3 percent from the same period in 1988.
</TEXT>
