<HEAD>Ferruzzi Says It Will Sue CBOT to Recover Damages</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 new grafs with Ferruzzi saying it will sue to recover
losses due to liquidation order. Picks up 4th graf pvs: ``U.S. District
...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HERBERT G. McCANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An Italian agribusiness firm said today it will go to court to recover losses resulting from an order by the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> forcing soybean traders from holding positions potentially large enough to corner the market. <PERSON> Raul </PERSON> <PERSON> Gardini </PERSON>, chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finanzaria </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> SpA </ORGANIZATION>, made the announcement in <LOCATION> Milan </LOCATION>. He reiterated the company's position that the accumulation of soybean contracts was legal, adding, `` <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> and all major world traders are convinced that the board made a mistake and has to suffer the consequences.'' <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> did n't specify the amount of losses suffered as a result of the board's order. But it said damages could be calculated in part as the difference between the closing market price of $ 7.26 a bushel on Tuesday, when the <ORGANIZATION> CBOT </ORGANIZATION> issued its order, and the price during the days through July 20, when all soybean traders must reduce their holdings to a maximum 1 million bushels. A spokesman said the suit probably would be filed in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, but did not give a timetable. The company also indicated it might seek compensation for unrealized profits as well as damage to its reputation. One day earlier, a federal judge denied a request by two <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> subsidiaries _ <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trading </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> SA </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> USA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> _ for a restraining order and a permanent injunction ending the <ORGANIZATION> BOT </ORGANIZATION>'s directive. Published reports have said the <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> was the object of the directive. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Zagel </PERSON> on Thursday denied the injunction request, saying the harm to public confidence in the Board of Trade from the injunction would surpass any monetary loss by <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION>. `` If I grant a temporary restraining order in this case and it turns out to be a mistake, -LRB- then -RRB- a possible default in the market, a loss of confidence in the market could be a consequence,'' <PERSON> Zagel </PERSON> said. CBOT <PERSON> Karsten </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahlmann </PERSON> said <PERSON> Zagel </PERSON>'s decision `` reaffirms that the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> has the authority to ensure the orderliness of the market and to effect the orderly liquidation of the July soybean contract.'' Soybean futures prices fell in early trading today in reaction to <PERSON> Zagel </PERSON>'s ruling. The July contract opened at $ 6.90 a bushel, 7 -LCB- cents below Thursday's settlement price. On Tuesday, the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>, the world's largest market for grain and soybean futures, issued an emergency order requiring any player holding obligations to receive or deliver more than 3 million bushels of soybeans for July delivery to reduce those holdings to 1 million bushels by the end of trading next Thursday, when the July contract expires. In issuing the order, the exchange cited federal regulations that allow it to take such action to ensure the orderly expiration of a futures contract. <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION>'s lawsuit claimed it had been irreparably injured by the order, which it said would diminish confidence in the market and hurt <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> farmers. In arguments before <PERSON> Zagel </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> lawyer <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Fox </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> acted `` arbitrarily and capriciously'' and in bad faith when it issued the order. <PERSON> Fox </PERSON> noted that the exchange ignored the fact that the market has been trading in a very narrow range in recent weeks, an indication that there was no squeeze or cornering of the market. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Angle </PERSON>, an attorney for the <ORGANIZATION> CBOT </ORGANIZATION>, argued that there `` is absolutely nothing in the record to show this action resulted from bad faith tantamount to fraud on the part of the CBOT.'' Angle said <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> could appeal the emergency order to the <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trading </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, which regulates the CBOT. Although he refused to grant an injunction, <PERSON> Zagel </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> CBOT </ORGANIZATION>'s action may not have been totally defensible He said <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> could sue and be adequately compensated for any loss in monetary damages if it proves its case. <PERSON> Fox </PERSON>, said he did not know whether the Italian firm would pursue the lawsuit or seek monetary damages. <PERSON> Zagel </PERSON> told attorneys for the <ORGANIZATION> CBOT </ORGANIZATION> to file a motion to dismiss the lawsuit by Tuesday, with a response due July 24. During the hearing before <PERSON> Zagel </PERSON>, <PERSON> Fox </PERSON> said the emergency order forced the Italian firm to reduce its holdings of July soybean contracts by 20 percent on Wednesday and another 20 percent Thursday. In related developments, the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Soybean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> called for an investigation of the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>'s directive and the <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> agriculture commissioner asked the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> to check whether <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> officials may have benefited from the effects of the order. Soybean futures gained Thursday on news that <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> had requested the restraining order, with the July contract closing up 10 cents at $ 6.96 a bushel. The market closed at $ 7.26 a bushel Tuesday before the CBOT liquidation order took effect.
