<FIRST>u f AM-Britain-BAT Bjt   07-14 0630</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-BAT, Bjt,0656</SECOND>
<HEAD>BAT Offer Pulls London's Stock Market Out of The Doldrums</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The hostile $ 21 billion bid for <ORGANIZATION> BAT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION> has pulled <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s stock market out of its recent doldrums by sparking speculation about which companies might be the next targets of takeovers. Share prices have jumped to post-crash highs and trading volume has soared on the <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> as investors have scrambled to place their bets. `` You've got bid fever,'' said <PERSON> Jeffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>, chief equity strategist at the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Barclays </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Zoete </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wedd </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd </ORGANIZATION>. The market is `` sizing up every possible target however remote, and taking it higher.'' But analysts said the euphoria could be short-lived. Still, the activity was raising hopes that business in general would pick up in the City of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the financial district, bringing in more fees and commissions. Investment firms have been feeling the squeeze since the October 1987 stock market crash and following the so-called Big Bang deregulation of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s financial markets nearly three years ago. No one, however, was saying that this sudden takeover speculation was going to be the City's cure-all. `` All the stockbroking houses have tremendous cost problems. It's going to take more of a surge than we've seen to overcome them,'' said an analyst who did not want to be identified `` Competition is pretty fierce,'' she said, `` You will have to have some people drop out.'' <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON>, a banking analyst with the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> investment firm <PERSON> Laing </PERSON> and <PERSON> Cruickshank </PERSON>, said the excitement `` delays a clean-out of the City.'' On Friday, the <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times-Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> 100-share index gained 15.7 points, or 0.7 percent, to finish at 2,273.7, a post-crash high. The index has risen 78.5 points, or 3.6 percent, since the market closed on Monday, the day before the bid for BAT Industries was announced. Volume amounted to a healthy 771.8 million shares on Friday. By comparison, June's average daily volume was 410 million shares. The hostile bid for the diversified British conglomerate was made by an investment group made up of Anglo-French financier Sir <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldsmith </PERSON>, <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> merchant banker <PERSON> Jacob </PERSON> <PERSON> Rothschild </PERSON> and Australian entrepreneur <PERSON> Kerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Packer </PERSON>. They want to break up BAT and sell off its non-tobacco interests: financial services, retailing and paper. Suddenly anything was possible on this side of the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> and the City buzzed with names of other potential targets. They included: _ <ORGANIZATION> Cadbury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Schweppes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>, the confectionery and soft drinks group _ <ORGANIZATION> Trafalgar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>, a shipping group _ <ORGANIZATION> Allied-Lyons </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>, the liquor company _ Hotel operator <ORGANIZATION> Trusthouse </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forte </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION> _ <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>, a retailer not related to the similarly named <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> company _ <ORGANIZATION> Grand </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Metropolitan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>, a liquor <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s market has been languishing since the stock market crash, plagued by weak prices and low trading volume. It has not recovered from the crash as well as the other major markets. British and foreign investment firms, which had geared up so eagerly for Big Bang, have found it extremely difficult to make profits. Commissions have declined because of the larger number of players vying for shrinking business. Firms have withdrawn from certain activities, like making markets in stocks and bonds, which had been opened up to them under Big Bang. They also have sought to cut their costs by cutting back staff and salaries. <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> said that despite the pickup in recent activity, `` We retain our cautious stance on the market.'' `` The nature of bid activity is that once that the action and the excitement is out of the way, the market tends to sag back,'' he said. `` Certain stocks are vulnerable in the shorter-term unless another megabid appears in the next few weeks to keep the momentum going.'' The strategist added that profit-taking could accelerate, a development that could depress prices.
</TEXT>
