<HEAD>McDonald's Tests Offering Pizza</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OWENSBORO, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The same people who brought you McNuggets and McRibs are testing a new product _ `` McPizza.'' <ORGANIZATION> McDonald </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which operates the nation's largest fast-food restaurant chain, will begin test marketing its 14-inch traditional pizzas at four stores in <LOCATION> Owensboro </LOCATION> within about 60 days, a spokesman said. A new McDonald's in <LOCATION> Evansville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ind. </LOCATION>, on Monday became the first in the country to test the pizza, said <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Cross </PERSON>, operations manager for the company's <LOCATION> Evansville </LOCATION> market. The four stores in <LOCATION> Owensboro </LOCATION> are undergoing construction to enlarge the kitchens to allow room for forced hot air ovens and windows that let people watch the pizza being made. Many restaurants serve pizza in 30 minutes. McDonald's will serve a pizza in five minutes, <PERSON> Cross </PERSON> said. The pizza will have a thin crust and come in four varieties _ cheese, pepperoni, sausage and deluxe. Employees will be trained to make the pizzas in the restaurants. <PERSON> Melissa </PERSON> <PERSON> Oakley </PERSON>, spokeswoman at the company's headquarters in <LOCATION> Oak </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Brook </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, said it's too early to know whether pizza will become a regular feature. `` McDonald's is excited with the idea of pizza,'' she said. `` It's a big business out there, and we're ready to get a piece of that pie.''
