<HEAD>Bond Agency Cuts Massachusetts Credit Rating Again</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 8th graf pvs, Saying it ... to CORRECT to show temporary
tax hike only deals with fiscal 1989 and medicaid bills. Picks up 9th graf
pvs, Standard &amp; ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Citing financial disarray in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> government, a major bond rating agency cut the state's credit rating Friday for the second time this year, a move that could add millions to borrowing costs. The decision by <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Poor </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> to downgrade <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> bonds from AA - to A represents a harsh assessment of the fiscal policies of Gov <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and the state Legislature. `` The state's economy remains strong, while debt and fiscal management display serious weaknesses,'' the agency said. `` The low state general obligation rating reflects <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; P's continuing concern about the willingness of the state to adhere to sound fiscal practices and timely financial decision making,'' it added Calls made to <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' office were not immediately returned Friday and a spokesman for state Administration and <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Lashman </PERSON> said there would be no comment. <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Poor's ratings are a measure of the risk associated with buying the state's bonds. The lower the rating, the higher the interest rate the state must offer investors to entice them to buy <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> bonds. The state treasurer's office estimates that the latest downgrade will cost the commonwealth about $ 2 million in interest payments over the next 12 months. But the combined cost of all the downgrades this year will be at least $ 20 million, said Deputy State Treasurer <PERSON> Cathy </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheppard </PERSON>. <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> ended its last fiscal year on June 30 with a deficit and unpaid Medicaid bills expected to total between $ 450 million and $ 500 million. Saying it was `` the worst thing I've ever had to do in my political career,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> on Thursday announced $ 491 million in cuts from the state's current budget. At the same time, the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> voted to raise the state income tax by 15 percent for 18 months to cover the deficit from the past fiscal year and pay old Medicaid bills. <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Poor's said it was assessing the viability of the governor's budget package but was uncertain of the legislature's response Democratic leaders in the state <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Representatives </ORGANIZATION> have said they will move to override the governor's veto of $ 210 million in state aid to cities and towns. `` With a number of issues still unresolved, such as the amount of local aid and the tax package, <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; P again observes a lack of timely financial decision making,'' the agency said. S & amp; P had previously downgraded <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> bonds from AA to AA-in early June. <ORGANIZATION> Moody </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>, another major bond rating agency, also cut its rating last month. S & amp; P's downgrading applies to $ 4.8 billion of <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> general obligation bonds and $ 1.4 billion in bonds issued by various state agencies. In addition, $ 757 million of general obligation notes and $ 710 million of various agencies' notes were lowered from SP1 + to SP1
