<HEAD>Petroluem Prices Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Energy futures finished lower Friday in a light, lackluster session with the heaviest selling in the gasoline trading pits. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the August contract for <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intermediate </ORGANIZATION>, which rose 20 cents on Thursday, lost 3 cents to settle at $ 20.32 per 42-gallon barrel. Most other contract months of the benchmark <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> grade of crude posted slightly bigger declines. Refined petroleum products traded on the exchange turned in similar performances. The August contract for home heating oil slid 0.11 cent to 49.33 cents a gallon, after rising 0.50 cent on Thursday. Contracts for delivery in more distant months settled with minor losses and gains. Wholesale unleaded gasoline for August delivery dropped 0.62 cent to 56.84 a gallon, erasing much of the combined gain of 0.84 cent over the previous two sessions. Smaller declines were posted by other gas contract months. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connell </PERSON>, an assistant vice president at <ORGANIZATION> Refco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said there was n't any overwhelmingly bearish news to account for the downturn in prices. A report circulating in the market that <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> might not reduce its oil production as much as previously indicated was the only disturbing factor for oil traders, <PERSON> O'Connell </PERSON> said. Otherwise, he said, prices may have sagged in the absence of many traders willing to support them with new buying before the weekend. `` It's Friday afternoon in July, there's not a lot of people around,'' said <PERSON> O'Connell </PERSON>.
</TEXT>
