<HEAD>Dollar Rises Despite Bearish Economic Data</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede: LONDON</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar gained ground Friday against all major currencies except the Canadian dollar in defiance of a slew of statistics that indicated the economy is cooling off. Gold prices fell sharply. On the Commodity Exchange in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, gold bullion for current delivery fell $ 6.20 a troy ounce to $ 370.80. <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> quoted a bid of $ 370.50 for an ounce of bullion at 4 p.m. EDT, down from Thursday's late bid of $ 375.50. Four sets of economic figures for June painted a picture of a sluggish economy: producer prices fell 0.1 percent, retail sales fell 0.4 percent, industrial production declined 0.2 percent, and the nation's factories, utilities and mines operated at a seasonally adjusted capacity of 83.5 percent, down from 83.8 percent in May. Typically such news would send the dollar lower on speculation that the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> would continue easing its hold on interest rates. But dealers said the fact that the dollar did n't fall much immediately after the figures were released encouraged players to buy the currency. `` It's the old story of selling on the rumor and buying on the fact,'' said <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Flanagan </PERSON>, a vice president at <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hanover </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. Traders sold dollars throughout the week on the expectation that the numbers would be weak `` When they came out and they were weak, everybody was looking to buy back dollars at the same time,'' <PERSON> Flanagan </PERSON> said. Trading was volatile and heavy, dealers said. <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Barbanel </PERSON>, a senior vice president at <ORGANIZATION> Gruntal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, noted that the market had `` hidden expectations'' of more dramatic data. He noted that further data due out next week, particuarly the merchandise trade numbers for June, will `` create -LRB- additional -RRB- trading opportunities,'' given the market's `` love affair with numbers.'' Statements coming out of the <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Seven </ORGANIZATION> industrialized nations also gave the dollar a boost. Comments that the finance ministers are satisfied with the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency's current level prompted traders to speculate that an even higher dollar might be tolerated. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, the dollar closed at 139.50 Japanese yen, up 0.45 yen from late Thursday. Later in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the dollar traded higher at 140.40 yen. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, the dollar closed at 140.85 yen, up from Thursday's 139.45 yen. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the dollar gained against the British pound. It cost $ 1.6125 to buy one pound, cheaper than $ 1.6240 late Thursday. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, one pound cost $ 1.6050, less expensive than Thursday's $ 1.6205. Other late dollar rates in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, compared with late Thursday's rates, included: 1.9125 West German marks, up from 1.8885; 1.6515 Swiss francs, up from 1.6300; 6.4890 French francs, up from 6.4085; 1,385.00 Italian lire, up from 1,369.50, and 1.1917 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1930. Late dollar rates in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, compared with late Thursday, included: 1.9030 West German marks, up from 1.8815; 1.6455 Swiss francs, up from 1.6190; 6.4575 French francs, up from 6.3870; 2.1400 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1155; 1,378.50 Italian lire, up from 1,362.25, and 1.1916 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1922. Gold fell in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to a late bid price of $ 370.50 a troy ounce, compared with late Thursday's $ 375.75. In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, gold fell to close at a bid of $ 370.75, compared with $ 375.75 late Thursday. Earlier in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold closed at $ 377.39 bid, down from $ 377.87 on Thursday. Silver bullion prices rose on the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> market, where the metal was trading at a late bid price of $ 5.25 a troy ounce, compared with Thursday's $ 5.20. On <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Comex, silver bullion for current delivery closed at $ 5.207 a troy ounce, up from Thursday's settlement of $ 5.195
