<SECOND>AM-Gas Conference,0368</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pickens Says Best Energy Policy Is No Policy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> oil magnate <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Boone </PERSON> <PERSON> Pickens </PERSON> said Friday the best thing <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> can do to promote the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> natural gas industry is to keep its hands off. `` Energy policy to some is for <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to give a tariff on imported oil. This I am against _ that is not an energy policy,'' <PERSON> Pickens </PERSON> told a conference on natural gas. `` My message to our leaders in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> is this: Thanks for decontrol of natural gas. Now leave the industry alone. We can take care of ourselves,'' he said. <PERSON> Pickens </PERSON> spoke at a two-day symposium on natural gas at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> that ended Friday. The conference drew legislators, environmentalists, scientists and energy industry experts. <PERSON> Pickens </PERSON>, founder and chief executive officer of <ORGANIZATION> Mesa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, said demand for gas is lagging far behind available supply, making it a bargain alternative to oil-based fuels. `` That's good news for energy security and the environment. That's not good news for the producers _ like me,'' he said. <PERSON> Pickens </PERSON> said the price of natural gas would have to double from current levels to be as costly as oil. But oversupply has put a stop to exploratory drilling, he said. <LOCATION> Mesa </LOCATION>, based in <LOCATION> Amarillo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, bolstered its natural gas investment before the petroleum market began to sour in 1986. Since 1985, <LOCATION> Mesa </LOCATION> has doubled its natural gas reserve base to an estimated 2.85 trillion cubic feet, <PERSON> Pickens </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> Railroad Commissioner <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Sharp </PERSON> said <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>'s market potential could pull the <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> petroleum industry out of a slump. He said projects in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> could bring <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> more than $ 3 billion in sales revenue in the next five years. `` We're in a downturn because of the oil crash, but we believe natural gas is going to become our golden goose,'' <PERSON> Sharp </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Sharp </PERSON> said he, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> Assembly Speaker <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, Jr. and Rep. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, D-Mass., had agreed to form a panel to consult with state legislators nationwide to draft a national clean air plan relying on natural gas
