<SECOND>AM-Mortgage Rates, 1st Ld-Writethru,f0150,0587</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fixed-Rate Mortgages Hit 2-year Low; VA Lowers Rate</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout with VA lowering rate. Also moving on general news
wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<UNK>Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Fixed-rate mortgages dropped to the lowest point in more than two years this week and in response the <ORGANIZATION> Veterans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Friday it is lowering the interest rate cap for VA-backed mortgages to 9.5 percent. Fixed-rate, 30-year mortgages averaged 9.82 percent this week, down from 10.03 percent last week, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mortgage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, known as <ORGANIZATION> Freddie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mac </ORGANIZATION>. The government-created company, which finances the housing market by purchasing mortgages, said it was the lowest weekly average since the week ending April 10, 1987. One-year, adjustable-rate mortgages fell to 8.73 percent this week, down from 8.85 percent a week earlier. Freddie Mac averages do not include special add-on fees known as points. The <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> said it was making the change in its rate, which will take effect Monday, to reflect the recent interest rate decline in financial markets. As a service to veterans, the <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> insures low-down-payment mortgages offered by private lenders and it sets a maximum rate to ensure that veterans are not paying more than rates on privately insured mortgages. The change brings the <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> rate to the lowest level in 16 months. The last change in the rate occurred June 5, when it went dropped to 10 percent from 10.5 percent, where it had been fixed since Dec. 19. `` This is certainly good news for the veteran who plans to purchase a home in the months ahead,'' <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Derwinski </PERSON> said in a statement. `` For many veterans, it means they may be able to buy homes that were beyond their means previously.'' Also effective Monday, the <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> will decrease other maximum rates by half a percentage point, including: graduated payment mortgages, to 9.75 percent; home improvement loans, to 12 percent, and mobile lot and home loans, to 11.5 percent. Economist <PERSON> Lyle </PERSON> <PERSON> Gramley </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Mortgage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bankers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> predicted that fixed-rate mortgages would fall by another quarter to half percentage point by the end of the year. `` That's not a large decline, but every little bit helps the housing market,'' he said. Housing has been one of the softest sectors in the economy this year because the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, until recently, has been nudging interest rates higher to curb inflation pressures. Since early June, the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> has reversed course, pushing short-term rates down by a half a percentage point. <PERSON> Gramley </PERSON> said he expected a further loosening in short-term rates from the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> of a quarter to a half percentage point by the end of the month, but that would not necessarily translate into a drop in adjustable-rate mortgages. `` More and more, the S & amp; Ls that were offering extremely attractive first-year teaser rates are no longer doing so because the federal presence in that industry is discouraging that,'' he said. Meanwhile, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, which does include points in its averages, said Friday that fixed-rate mortgages averaged 11.00 percent in early June, down from 11.49 percent in early May. It was the lowest since the rates averaged 10.87 percent in December. The most popular type of adjustable-rate mortgage, the type with caps on how high the rate can rise, averaged 10.05 percent in early June, down from 10.28 percent in May. It was the first drop since October.
