<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Gold futures prices tumbled more than $ 6 an ounce Friday on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Commmodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> on expectations that investment demand for the metal will fall following government reports indicating an economic slowdown. On other markets, orange juice futures plunged; grains and soybeans were higher; energy futures were mixed; and livestock and meat futures were mixed. Gold settled $ 6.10 to $ 6.40 lower with the contract for delivery in August at $ 372.20 a troy ounce. Silver was 0.8 cent to 1.5 cents higher with July at $ 5.207 a troy ounce. Analysts attributed gold's retreat mainly to the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s report of a 0.1 percent decline in wholesale prices in June. The market had been expecting the report to show an increase of 0.1 percent to 0.3 percent. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s report of a 0.4 percent drop in retail sales last month _ making for the first back-to-back drop in more than two years _ was also discouraging to gold traders. But the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION>'s report of slowing industrial production and factory use sent a mixed message to the inflation-sensitive gold market, suggesting both a reduction in inflationary pressures _ which is bearish for gold _ and the possibility that the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> will continue to ease up on interest rates, which is bullish for gold. `` The economic reports were not all that bearish,'' said <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Demler </PERSON>, metals economist with <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Demler </PERSON> pointed out that gold prices had risen by about $ 20 an ounce since early June and said that when the wholesale-prices report came out Friday morning, `` traders saw it as an opportunity to take profits.'' Frozen concentrated orange juice futures fell the permitted 5-cents-a-pound daily limit on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cotton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> and the soon-to-expire July contract, which has no limit, plunged 6.3 cents to settle at $ 1.7135 a pound. Analysts linked the sharp drop to rumors that a large <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> processor planned to cut prices due to a large Brazilian orange crop. Grain and soybean futures prices finished moderately higher on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> on bullish weather forecasts and indications of Soviet purchases of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> soybean meal. Soybean traders shifted their attention back to supply-and-demand factors after focusing for two days on wrangling between the exchange and a large Italian company over the exchange's demand that traders reduce their holdings in the July soybean contract. Soybean prices had fallen in early trading Friday following a federal court ruling Thursday evening that upheld the exchange's order Two subsidiaries of the Italian agribusiness firm <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finanziara </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> SpA </ORGANIZATION> had sought a court order blocking the directive, which <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> claimed was aimed at weakening its market position. Wheat settled 1 cent to 4 -LCB- cents higher with July at $ 3.95 \ a bushel; corn was -LCB- cent to 3 -LCB- cents higher with July at $ 2.59 -RCB- a bushel; oats were 2 \ cents higher across the board with July at $ 1.50 -LCB- a bushel; soybeans wer