man for <ORGANIZATION> Unisys </ORGANIZATION>, which was formed in 1986 when <ORGANIZATION> Burroughs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> acquired <PERSON> Sperry </PERSON>. According to court papers, <PERSON> Tomlin </PERSON>, who now lives near <LOCATION> Orlando </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, demanded $ 500,000 from <ORGANIZATION> Sperry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> in return for his influence in helping the company obtain lucrative contracts for computerized maintenance of electronic weapons components. The court papers revealed that the bribery arrangement was approved by an unidentified high-ranking official of <ORGANIZATION> Sperry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and was also known to an executive at the company's <LOCATION> Clearwater </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, electronics plant. The Clearwater executive told <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gardner </PERSON>, then a Sperry vice president in charge of the company's Surveillance and <ORGANIZATION> Fire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> Division in <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Neck </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, that <PERSON> Tomlin </PERSON> was ready to retire and `` wanted a nest egg.'' <PERSON> Gardner </PERSON>, who pleaded guilty to an unrelated bribery charge in March, obtained approval of the arrangement to pay <PERSON> Tomlin </PERSON> from his superior. Former <ORGANIZATION> Unisys </ORGANIZATION> marketing manager <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, 42, pleaded guilty to participating in a scheme to pay $ 4,000 in illegal corporate campaign contributions to <PERSON> Aspin </PERSON> and other <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> members. <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, who worked with <PERSON> Gardner </PERSON>, admitted directing private consultants to make the contributions as individuals with money they were paid by <ORGANIZATION> Unisys </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Unisys </ORGANIZATION> consultants <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Zuba </PERSON>, 67, of <LOCATION> Mechanicsburg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Gerard </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Scarano </PERSON>, 74, admitted participating in the scheme to conceal the illegal donations. Contributions were also made to Reps. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Roe </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.J. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Fla </LOCATION>., <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Hochbrueckner </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION> as well as former Rep. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Badham </PERSON>, R-Calif. and the late Rep. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Chappell </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Fla </LOCATION>., according to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Claude </PERSON> <PERSON> Hilton </PERSON> scheduled sentencings for the five defendants for Sept. 29.
