<HEAD>Bond Prices Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Bond prices sagged and long-term interest rates rose in volatile trading Friday as the government reported economic data that were n't weak enough to entice the credit markets. The <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>'s benchmark 30-year bond fell 13-32 point, or about $ 4 per $ 1,000 face amount. Its yield, which moves in the opposite direction from its price, climbed to 8.08 percent from 8.03 percent late Thursday. Initially, evidence of economic weakness furnished by government reports inspired buying enthusiasm in the bond market but the rally soon faded. In two separate reports, the government said retail sales fell 0.4 percent in June and the Producer Price Index dipped by 0.1 percent, the first decline in this inflation measure in 18 months. Also, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> industrial production fell 0.2 percent last month while <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> factories, mines and utilities used less of their operating capacity. Normally the credit market would welcome signs that a slowdown in economic activity is being accompanied by a moderation in inflation. But <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramirez </PERSON>, an economist at <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said the market had built up hopes ahead of the numbers and pushed up bond prices to very high levels. When the reports merely confirmed widely held views, traders decided to sell and collect profits. `` It's not that the market is falling apart, it's retrenching a little bit from very expensive levels,'' she said. <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> A </PERSON>. <PERSON> Wood </PERSON>, an economist, with <ORGANIZATION> BankAmerica </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Markets </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, said the rally fizzled as traders cashed in profits on the belief the recent rally would go no further. He also said the new figures were not weak enough to convince the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> to lower interest rates further. `` At the least the next official move is going to be several weeks off at the earliest,'' <PERSON> Wood </PERSON> said. In addition, he said the market was slowed by news that a <ORGANIZATION> House-Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> committee </ORGANIZATION> neared an agreement on a thrift bailout bill that would add $ 50 billion in financing to the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> market over three years. With a greater supply in the market, bond prices would likely drop. In the secondary market for <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bonds, prices of short-term governments fell 1-16 point, intermediate maturities were 3-32 point to \ point lower and long-term issues were down 5-16 point to 13-32 point, according to <ORGANIZATION> Telerate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the financial information service. The movement of a point is equivalent to a change of $ 10 in the price of a bond with a $ 1,000 face value. The <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> Bond Index, which measures price movements on all outstanding <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> issues with maturities of a year or longer, fell 1.96 to 1,189.14. In corporate trading, industrials slipped. <ORGANIZATION> Moody </ORGANIZATION>'s Investment Grade Corporate Bond Index, which measures total return on a portfolio of 80 corporate bonds with maturities of five years or longer, fell 0.17 to 329.87. In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively traded municipal bonds closed at 94 -RCB-, down -LRB-. The average yield to maturity rose to 7.18 percent from 7.17 percent late Thursday. Yields on three-month <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bills rose to 8.08 percent as the discount gained 6 basis points to 7.82 percent. Yields on six-month bills rose to 8.01 percent as the discount rose 8 basis points to 7.61 percent. Yields on one-year bills climbed to 7.85 percent as the discount gained 3 points to 7.33 percent. A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. The yield is the annualized return on an investment in a <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bill. The discount is the percentage that bills are selling below the face value, which is paid at maturity. The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between banks, traded at 93-16 percent, down from 95-16 percent late Thursday.
