<HEAD>Inland Ratifies Contract</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Members of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steelworkers </ORGANIZATION> union overwhelmingly ratified a four-year contract offer that improves wages and fringe benefits at <ORGANIZATION> Inland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, according to ballot tabulations Friday. At National, union members voted by an overwhelming 87 percent to accept an offer nearly identical to one they had rejected by 61 percent in June despite a recommendation to ratify from their negotiators. `` A no vote would have meant a debilitating strike that would have destroyed National's productivity and profits for the entire year,'' said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Coffee </PERSON>, vice president and chief company negotiator. National's 50-month contract provides immediate $ 500 signing bonuses, $ 500 advances on profit-sharing payments and base wage increases of 31 cents per hour. Wage increases totalling $ 1.50 will follow. At Inland, the vote was 7,909 to 586 to ratify base wage increases of $ 1.50, a $ 500 signing bonus, inflation recognition payments, an extra week of vacation and pensions of at least $ 1,000 per month for 30-year veterans. `` The sacrifices, dedication and hard work of our members have helped turn this company around, which is why we were determined to get a contract second to none,'' said <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Parton </PERSON>, director of <ORGANIZATION> USW </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> 31 </ORGANIZATION> and the union's chief negotiator with the nation's sixth-largest steelmaker `` We helped mix and bake the pie. Now we're getting our slice. What could be more American than that?'' he said in a printed statement. The new agreement takes effect Aug. 1 and expires July 31, 1983, for 11,500 <ORGANIZATION> USW </ORGANIZATION> members at Inland's major plant at <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, its <ORGANIZATION> Minorca </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mine </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minn. </LOCATION>, and the Inland Lime and <ORGANIZATION> Stone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Gulliver </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>. National employs about 7,000 union members at <LOCATION> Ecorse </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Granite </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, Ill, and <LOCATION> Portage </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ind </LOCATION> Officials of the <ORGANIZATION> USW </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Wheeling-Pittsburgh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, meanwhile, said they have asked a federal bankruptcy judge to approve hourly wage increases of 50 cents for union members at the financially troubled company. Judge <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentz </PERSON> scheduled a July 27 hearing on the issue. The request does not represent the opening of negotiations on a new contract. Rather, it reflects production records that have been set since the current pact was settled in October 1985. The agreement does not expire until <ORGANIZATION> Wheeling-Pittsburgh </ORGANIZATION> emerges from Chapter 11 reorganization.
