<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> lost a pivotal battle in its hostile $ 12.2 billion bid for <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> when a <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> judge refused to block Time's $ 14 billion tender offer for <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. But Chancery Court Judge <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> on Friday halted <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION>'s $ 70 a share offer, which had been scheduled to expire at midnight Monday, for 10 days to give Paramount time to appeal his ruling to the <ORGANIZATION> Delaware </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> later agreed to hear the case. If Paramount loses there it will pave the way for Time and <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> to merge, forming <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the world's largest communications concern.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Leaders of the world's seven richest nations, treated to the pomp and pageantry of the French bicentennial, got down to business as President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> scored an early victory on a contentious trade dispute with <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> but failed in efforts to speed approval of a Mexican debt deal. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, making his first appearance on the world economic stage, brought a full agenda of items Friday for discussion with the leaders of <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. The president discussed his just-completed trip to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> and sought agreement from the other countries for a coordinated assistance effort to both nations.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, trying to knock down the last hurdles to its new Third World debt strategy, has promised to arrange as much as $ 2 billion in loans for financially strapped <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, officials said. French President <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> said Friday that <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, burdened by a whopping $ 100 billion in foreign debt, urgently needs help.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Wholesale prices fell in June for the first time in 18 months while retail sales recorded the first back-to-back monthly declines since the 1987 stock market plunge, the government said. Prices one stop short of retail, as measured by the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s Producer Price Index, dropped 0.1 percent in June, driven down by tumbling energy and food costs, the government said Friday. It was the first decline since December 1987.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Retail sales fell 0.4 percent in June, dragged down by falling auto and home furnishing purchases, the government reported. Analysts said big-ticket items would continue to bear the brunt of the anti-inflation fight. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> reported Friday that sales fell to a seasonally adjusted $ 140.8 billion last month after dropping 0.1 percent in May. It was the first back-to-back monthly decline since 1987 when sales declined 0.8 percent in September and 0.9 percent in October.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Both the factory operating rate and industrial production fell last month, providing more evidence of a slowing economy caused by anti-inflation measures. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> said Friday the June operating rate declined to 83.5 percent, a 0.3 percentage point drop from May. The rate was 84.1 percent in April and hit a 10-year high of 84.3 percent in December. The <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> also said industrial production was off 0.2 percent last month, with its industrial production index standing at 141.1 percent of its 1977 base, down from May's 141.4 percent. It was the first decline since it fell 0.2 percent in February, which had been the first drop in a year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Italian agribusiness giant <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> plans to renew its court battle to recover losses stemming from a <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> order forcing soybean traders to liquidate large positions in the market. <PERSON> Raul </PERSON> <PERSON> Gardini </PERSON>, chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finanzaria </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> SpA </ORGANIZATION>, reiterated Friday in <LOCATION> Milan </LOCATION> that his company's accumulation of futures contracts to take delivery of 23 million bushels of soybeans was legal. A Feruzzi spokesman said a lawsuit probably would be filed in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, but did not provide a timetable. The company also indicated it might seek compensation for unrealized profits as well as damage to its reputation.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Congressional negotiators, breaking a procedural deadlock, have tentatively agreed to toughen proposed regulations on savings and loans as part of a $ 157 billion taxpayer bailout of the industry. Although nothing was adopted, <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> conferees Friday moved toward embracing a combination of the toughest specific capital requirements in separate <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> bills to make S & amp; Ls back up loans with more of their own money.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Citing financial disarray in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>' government, a major bond rating agency cut the state's credit rating for the second time this year, a move that could add millions to borrowing costs The decision Friday by <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Poor </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> to downgrade <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> bonds from AA - to A represents a harsh assessment of the fiscal policies of Gov <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and the state Legislature.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By The Associated Press</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 The stock market ran its July record to nine gains in nine sessions with an afternoon advance Friday. The Dow Jones industrials average rose 16.50 to a new post-crash high of 2,554.82, extending its gain for the week to 66.96 points. The dollar gained ground against all major currencies except the Canadian dollar. Bond prices fell. Gold futures prices tumbled more than $ 6 an ounce; orange juice futures plunged; grains and soybeans were higher; energy futures were mixed; and livestock and meat futures were mixed.
