<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> NEW </LOCATION> <LOCATION> YORK </LOCATION> _ These are some of the key developments in the takeover battle surrounding <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>: Nov. 10, 1988 _ Time Chairman <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Munro </PERSON>, hinting at plans for an acquisition or merger, tells securities analysts <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> intends to become a global media conglomerate. March 4, 1989 _ Time and <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> announce they will merge in a friendly stock swap to form <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the world's largest communications concern. April 9 _ <ORGANIZATION> Gulf </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Western </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> says it put its consumer finance segment, <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION>, up for sale, allowing the company to focus on its entertainment and publishing businesses. <ORGANIZATION> Gulf </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> says it will use some of the proceeds _ projected at $ 2.5 billion _ to finance acquisitions. May 22 _ Time and <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> schedule July 23 meetings for their shareholders to vote on the planned merger. June 5 _ <ORGANIZATION> Gulf </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION>, noting its focus on entertainment and media, announces it is changing its name to <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. June 6 _ Paramount announces a $ 10.7 billion, or $ 175 a share, offer for Time and files suit in <ORGANIZATION> Delaware </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chancery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> against the <ORGANIZATION> Time-Warner </ORGANIZATION> merger June 16 _ Time rejects <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION>'s offer as inadequate and highly conditional, announces it will pursue a $ 14 billion outright buyout of <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> and postpones its shareholders meeting until June 30. June 23 _ Paramount raises its bid for Time to $ 12.2 billion, or $ 200 a share. June 26 _ Time rejects <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION>'s sweetened bid and reiterates its intention to acquire <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION>. June 28 _ <ORGANIZATION> Delaware </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chancery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Judge <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> refuses to block Time's annual meeting. June 29 _ Paramount says seven banks have agreed to help raise the financing for its Time bid, although the company does not have commitments for all of the required backing. June 30 _ At Time's annual meeting, <PERSON> Munro </PERSON> states that the company is not for sale as shareholders press company officials on their decision not to consider the Paramount bid. July 7 _ Time announces it has financing commitments from 40 banks for its <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> bid. July 8 _ Time announces it has completed the financing commitments for the <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> offer with agreements from two investment firms. July 10 _ Paramount amends its offer to include an interest payment of 9 percent a year, or about $ 1.50 a month, to begin 60 days after Time agrees to a merger or is ordered to refrain from interfering with the Paramount bid. July 11 _ <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> hears arguments on a request by <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> and some Time shareholders to halt the <ORGANIZATION> Time-Warner </ORGANIZATION> merger. July 14 _ <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> denies the Paramount and shareholder request for an injunction against <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION>'s tender offer for <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION>, but temporarily halts the bid to give the plaintiffs time to appeal.
