<HEAD>Big Real Estate Firm Seeks Bankruptcy Refuge Because of Crushing
Debts</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Adds 7 grafs background at end.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Southmark </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, a large real estate company plagued by indebtedness stemming partly from its reliance on junk-bond financing, filed Friday for federal bankruptcy protection from creditors. The troubled company had been attempting to avoid bankruptcy by restructuring its property and financial holdings, but a $ 1 billion first - quarter loss placed it in technical default on the junk bonds Creditors had begun taking steps to force the company into bankruptcy. The Chapter 11 bankruptcy filing is one of the largest ever by a company that used junk bonds as part of its financial strategy. Revco D.S. <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a national drugstore chain that relied on junk bonds in a debt-financed takeover, sought Chapter 11 bankruptcy a year ago after failing to make an interest payment on about $ 700 million in junk bonds. These bonds, commonly used by companies to bankroll expansion and acquisitions, are considered low-investment grade securities. They pay high rates of interest to compensate bondholders for the higher risk of buying them. <ORGANIZATION> Southmark </ORGANIZATION> has about 32,000 employees and 13,000 shareholders. Formerly known as Citizens and <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Realty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investors </ORGANIZATION>, the company buys, improves and sells real estate assets, manages apartments, nursing homes, shopping centers and office buildings, and owns <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jacinto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION>, the ninth-largest <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; L in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. `` <ORGANIZATION> Southmark </ORGANIZATION>'s previously disclosed forecasts show it can not continue to pay its interest and principal amortization obligations beyond Nov. 1, 1989,'' Chairman <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Weiss </PERSON> said in announcing the bankruptcy filing. `` It would be unfair to large portions of the company's constituencies to continue to pay the debt service in the interim, given all the circumstances. `` Accordingly, the board of directors has decided to discontinue its policy of paying all debt service as it comes due.'' Wall Street securities strategists that follow <ORGANIZATION> Southmark </ORGANIZATION> had been predicting bankruptcy was a strong possibility and warned clients to avoid the company's stock. `` We see scant appeal to the individual investor in these shares,'' <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON>, an analyst for the <ORGANIZATION> Value </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Line </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Survey </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, wrote in a June report about <LOCATION> thecompany </LOCATION>'s deteriorating financial condition <PERSON> Weiss </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Southmark </ORGANIZATION> will continue to operate while reorganizing, but could not predict when the company would emerge from bankruptcy. `` We chose reorganization through the court in light of our responsibilities to all of <ORGANIZATION> Southmark </ORGANIZATION>'s key constitutiencies _ creditors, stockholders and bondholders, employees, customers and business partners, and vendors and suppliers.'' As part of the filing, <ORGANIZATION> Southmark </ORGANIZATION> received agreement from the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> that as long as the company can meet regulatory capital requirements at <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jacinto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Savings </LOCATION> and Loan, the government will not seek to shut down the $ 3.5 billion-asset thrift. <PERSON> Weiss </PERSON> has said before he hopes to base <ORGANIZATION> Southmark </ORGANIZATION>'s resurgence on still-solvent <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jacinto </LOCATION>. The filing in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bankruptcy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, where the company is incorporated, lists assets of $ 1.05 billion and liabilities of $ 1.4 billion, including $ 1.05 billion in unsecured debt sold through <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a leading issuer and marketer of junk bonds. Under Chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy code, a company is protected from creditors while it devises a way to pay its debts and reorganize its business. <ORGANIZATION> Southmark </ORGANIZATION>, which began as a real estate investment trust operation of <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Citizens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, used the junk bonds to finance its rapid growth into a $ 8 billion-asset company with holdings from campgrounds to insurance companies and a range of real estate enterprises. However the company, which eventually moved to <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>, has been strapped by liquidity problems, as it became victimized by the <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION>'s real estate collapse and was left holding huge numbers of non-performing assets. The liquidity problems eventually led to the ouster in January of Chairman <PERSON> Gene </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON> and Vice Chairman <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Friedman </PERSON>, who were blamed for the situation. The board replaced with two with <PERSON> Weiss </PERSON>, a thrift executive from <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>. In the months since, the company has sold off about $ 170 million in assets to improve its cash position. `` We have improved liquidity through asset sales,'' <PERSON> Weiss </PERSON> said Friday, adding that the company had $ 85 million on hand to pay operating expenses. `` We will continue our program to sell selected assets,'' he said, leaving the company with a core of real estate and thrift operations. `` Without undue pressure from creditors, we can seek maximum value for these assets.'' The company said it would continue to seek buyers for its insurance, recreational land, health care and gaming interests.
